<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Bulgaria-Emissions     10-31 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bulgaria-Emissions,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12 Countries Sign Declaration To Reduce Nitrogen Oxide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve countries Monday signed a
declaration to reduce emissions of air pollutants that contribute
to acid rain and the depletion of the ozone layer.
   The countries that promised to reduce by 30 percent their
emissions of nitrogen oxide in the next 10 years are Finland,
Norway, Belgium, Italy, France, Austria, Switzerland, Sweden, West
Germany, Liechtenstein, Denmark and the Netherlands.
   Nitrogen oxide, derived mostly from car exhaust fumes and the
burning of fossil fuels, contributes to smog, acid rain and the
``greenhouse effect,'' or the warming of the atmosphere around
Earth.
   The 12 members of the United Nations Economic Commission for
Europe were in Sofia for a meeting of the Convention on Long-range
Transboundary Air Pollution that begins Tuesday.
</TEXT>
