<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1909EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Stereotyping     10-31 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Stereotyping,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employers Should Prove They Don't Discriminate Sexually, Court
Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, examining ``macho''
attitudes in the workplace, was told Monday that employers should
be under a heavy burden to disprove sexual stereotyping when
charged with discriminating against women.
   James Heller, representing a woman denied a partnership at one
of the nation's leading accounting firms, said employers should be
forced to show by ``clear and convincing evidence'' they did not
practice bias.
   Otherwise, Heller said, it will be impossible to pierce ``the
impenetrable ... smog'' surrounding motives for hiring, firing and
promotion decisions made in the ``collegial'' atmosphere of
business boardrooms.
   But Kathryn Oberly, a lawyer for the accounting firm Price
Waterhouse, said there was no solid evidence to show that sexual
stereotypin caused the company not to grant a partnership to the
former employee, Ann Hopkins.
   ``We have overwhelming evidence of legitimate motives,'' Ms.
Oberly said.
   She said lower court rulings in favor of Ms. Hopkins were like a
football game in which one side wins without even crossing midfield.
   ``The plaintiff must bring the ball over the 50-yard line,'' Ms.
Oberly said.
   The justices, who heard 60 minutes of arguments in the case, are
expected to announce a ruling by July.
   Ms. Hopkins quit Price Waterhouse, one of the nation's ``big
eight'' accounting firms, after she was denied promotion to
partnership in 1983 _ a move that would have made her a part owner.
   She later became a consultant to the World Bank.
   Ms. Hopkins had joined Price Waterhouse in 1978 and was
nominated for partnership in 1982, the only woman among 88
candidates for partnership that year.
   She had been successful in getting business for the company,
winning government contracts worth between $34 million and $44
million.
   According to court documents, both her critics and supporters at
Price Waterhouse said she sometimes was overly aggressive, too
harsh, impatient with her staff and very demanding.
   One critic suggested she needed to take a ``course at charm
school.''
   A partner who supported her for promotion told her she would
stand a better chance of getting ahead if she would ``walk more
femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear
make-up, have her hair styled and wear jewelry,'' the documents
said.
   Ms. Oberly said Monday that the comment was made by Ms. Hopkins'
strongest supporter at Price Waterhouse. It was ``his personal
reaction. He was not the decision-maker'' on her promotion, she
said.
   There is ``no linkage between those comments and the (alleged)
discrimination,'' Ms. Oberly said.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall asked whether there ``is any statement
in the record'' rebutting the charge that she would do better by
being ``less macho.''
   Ms. Oberly said that was not the point of her argument.
   ``That's my point,'' Marshall said.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, back on the bench after breast
cancer surgery 10 days ago, also took an active part in questioning
the lawyers.
   She asked whether ``maybe the burden (of proof) shifts at some
time to the employer'' to disprove sexual stereotyping charges.
   Ms. Hopkins sued Price Waterhouse on grounds it violated Title
VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act prohibiting on-the-job
discrimination. She said sexual stereotyping, unconscious or
otherwise, cost her a partnership.
   Professional partnerships are covered by the 1964 law under a
1984 Supreme Court ruling.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington ruled in 1987
that if there were mixed motives in denying Ms. Hopkins a
partnership Price Waterhouse was unable to prove that
``impermissible bias was not the determinative factor'' for the
decision.
   The appeals court ordered further hearings to determine what
remedies were due Ms. Hopkins and what the penalties should be
against the accounting firm.
   The case is Price Waterhouse vs. Hopkins, 87-1167.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
