<2ND_LINE>AM-Cotton Program,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cotton Farmers Must Double Acreage Cuts For 1989 Supports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cotton farmers will have to reduce their 1989
acreage 25 percent to qualify for federal price supports, double
this year's requirement of 12.5 percent, Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng announced Monday.
   Unlike grain and soybeans, cotton suffered minimal damage from
this year's drought. Exports are down, and this year's harvest far
exceeds projected cotton use in 1988-89, according to Agriculture
Department analysts.
   Lyng said the established target price for upland cotton will be
73.4 cents per pound and that the price support loan level will be
50 cents per pound for the base quality of upland cotton.
   There will be no paid ``land-diversion'' for idling land under
the 1989 program, he said.
