<DOCNO> AP881031-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1910EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Houseman-ActingCompany     10-31 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Houseman-Acting Company,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Acting Company Remains as John Houseman's Legacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Houseman Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When members of the Acting Company heard of John
Houseman's death, they were doing what they do for much of the year
_ acting on the road.
   The touring repertory company, founded by Houseman and Margot
Harley, was in Missouri, appearing in the 1940s comedy ``Boy Meets
Girl'' at the Repertory Theater of St. Louis.
   The troupe of actors, currently 10 men and five women, was a
special joy for Houseman, the author, director, actor and producer
who died Monday at the age of 86.
   It was an idea born during Houseman's leadership at the Drama
Division of the Juilliard School in New York, a job he held for
eight years.
   ``The idea of creating of a company out of a school really isn't
a unique one,'' Harley said Monday. ``We hadn't planned to do it
but our first class was so astounding. They had created this
incredible ensemble as well as being individually talented.''
   The seed for the Acting Company blossomed in December 1971 when
fourth year students in the Drama Division presented a four-day
festival of theater. It was diverse program by the school's first
graduating class and included such work as ``The Lower Depths,''
``The School for Scandal,'' ``Women Beware Women'' and ``The Indian
Wants the Bronx.''
   The critics cheered, and Houseman decided to put into motion a
plan that had been percolating in the back of his mind for some
time _ a permanent, touring repertory company, made up of Juilliard
graduates.
   ``The Acting Compay fulfills a very important dual function,''
Houseman said in an interview with The Associated Press four years
ago. ``It provides pretty good performances of important plays and
does them all over the country, even in places that never get any
theater, except what we bring them.
   ``And it fulfills a secondary function, which, in a way, has
become equally important,'' he said. ``It's a training ground for
young star actors. The results are extraordinary.''
   Graduates of the Acting Company continue to make their mark in
the theater, movies and television. The first troupe included Patti
LuPone, Broadway's ``Evita'' and currently starring at Lincoln
Center in a revival of ``Anything Goes.'' Kevin Kline, the dashing
pirate king of ``The Pirates of Penzance'' and the looney con man
of the film ``A Film Called Wanda'' also was a member of the
initial company.
   Today, you can find other talented Acting Company alums
everywhere _ like Benjamin Hendrickson, a leading player on
television's ``As the World Turns''; Frances Conroy in the latest
Woody Allen film ``Another Woman'' and the new Lincoln Center
revival of ``Our Town''; David Ogden Stiers, also in the Allen
movie as well as a star at the Old Globe Theater in San Diego, and
Lisa Banes on Broadway in Neil Simon's comedy ``Rumors.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1718EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FarmPrices     10-31 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Prices,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>October Prices for Farm Products Up 13 Percent Over Year Earlier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products in October
held steady at their late-summer level but still averaged 13
percent more than they did a year ago, the Agriculture Department
said Monday.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said in its
preliminary report that higher prices for oranges, milk, lettuce
and corn were offset by lower prices for tomatoes, apples, eggs and
soybeans.
   Meanwhile, prices paid by farmers to meet expenses _ a figure
computed only every three months _ rose 1.2 percent from July and
averaged 5.5 percent more than a year ago.
   Farmers paid more for feeder cattle and calves than they did in
July, but feed and fuels were lower, the report said.
   Prices received by farmers for some major commodities are based
on mid-month averages and then are revised the following month when
additional information is available.
   The revised figures showed the leveling off actually began in
September when the price index held steady at its August average.
The preliminary reading for October continued at the
August-September level.
   Prices of raw farm commodities began rising in May as the
drought worsened and continued climbing in June, July and August,
an increase of about 11 percent from last April.
   After holding steady during most of last winter, the USDA index
rose 3.1 percent from April to May, followed by June, 2.2 percent;
July 2.9 percent; and August 2.1 percent.
   The drought and searing heat during the spring and summer cut
1988 harvest prospects sharply and triggered the midyear price
rise. Total U.S. grain production is expected to be down 31 percent
from last year's harvest.
   Despite the leveling of the overall price index, some
commodities continued higher in October. Wheat, for example, rose
an additional 14 cents per bushel to a U.S. farm price average of
$3.89 per bushel, the most since it was $3.95 in May 1981.
   Prices of livestock and livestock products as a group were
unchanged from September, although dairy products gained 3.1
percent during the month and the index for poultry and eggs
declined 5 percent. Compared with October 1987, the index was up
4.1 percent.
   The department's all-crops price index for October, although
unchanged from September, was up 27 percent from a year earlier.
Prices of feed grain and hay as a group rose 1.5 percent from
September and averaged 62 percent more than in October 1987.
   Prices of commercial vegetables were down 5 percent from
September but were still 8.2 percent more than a year ago.
   Although the projections are subject to change, USDA economists
say that net cash income of farmers may be in the range of $55
billion to $60 billion this year, compared with the record level of
$57.1 billion in 1987. That is the difference between cash receipts
and cash expenses during the calendar year.
   Department economists are holding to an earlier prediction that
consumer food prices will rise 3 percent to 5 percent this year,
compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987. Before the
drought took hold, USDA was predicting a 1988 food price hike of 2
percent to 4 percent.
   Some USDA officials also have predicted that the drought may add
2 percentage points to food prices in 1989, above the expected
increase in inflation, currently forecast at around 4 percent. That
could mean a 1989 food price increase in the range of 6 percent to
7 percent.
   The report said:
   _Cattle averaged $67.90 per 100 pounds of live weight
nationally, up from $67.20 in September and $62.90 reported for
October 1987. Those are averages for all types of cattle sold as
beef.
   _Hogs averaged $39.40 per 100 pounds, compared with $40.70 in
September and $48.90 a year earlier.
   _Corn, at $2.71 a bushel, was up from $2.60 in September and the
average of $1.55 per bushel a year earlier.
   _Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures,
averaged $3.89 per bushel, compared with $3.75 in September and
$2.62 a year earlier.
   _Rice averaged $7.15 per 100 pounds, compared with $6.82 in
September and $5.88 a year earlier.
   _Soybeans were $7.71 per bushel, compared with $7.94 in
September and $5.04 a year earlier.
   _Upland cotton was reported at 50 cents per pound, compared with
51.8 in September and 65.1 cents in October 1987.
   _Eggs were 58.7 cents per dozen, compared with 63.8 cents in
September and 50.2 cents a year earlier.
   _Milk was $12.80 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.40 in
September and $12.90 a year earlier.
   _Broilers were 37.5 cents per pound, live weight, compared with
39.2 cents in September and 25.1 cents a year ago.
</TEXT>
