<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Metzenbaum-KraftTakeover     10-31 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Metzenbaum-Kraft Takeover,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum Questions Kraft-Philip Morris Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The multibillion-dollar merger of Kraft Inc.
and Philip Morris Cos. Inc. could harm consumers, Sen. Howard M.
Metzenbaum said Monday in calling on the Federal Trade Commission
to launch an antitrust investigation.
   Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, called for the inquiry in a letter directed
to FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver, in which the senator said food
prices could go higher if the merger is allowed to go through.
   By creating the second largest food company in the world the
merger could seriously affect competition and sale of prepared
foods, said Metzenbaum, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
subcommittee on antitrust, monopolies and business rights.
   FTC spokesman Howard Shapiro said the agency would not comment
on whether it was looking into the merger.
   The proposed $13.1 billion buyout of Kraft by Philip Morris
would create the world's largest consumer products company.
   The planned merger, announced Sunday, would create a $40
billion-a-year company armed with some of America's best-known
consumer products, including Miller beer, Marlboro cigarettes,
Jell-O, Maxwell House coffee, Velveeta cheese, Parkay margarine,
Philadelphia cream cheese, Miracle Whip salad dressing and Sealtest
ice cream.
   The FTC and the Justice Department share responsibility for
policing the antitrust laws. Investigations, which can lead to a
merger being blocked, are not made public.
</TEXT>
