<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     10-31 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Prime Minister To Visit U.N. This Week.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name for Najib in 5th graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan Prime Minister Hassan Sharq will
visit the U.N. this week, and anti-communist rebels fighting
Afghanistan's Marxist government said Monday they would send
representatives to the world body.
   The General Assembly is expected to adopt a resolution welcoming
the Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan. It has adopted
resolutions annually denouncing the Soviet intervention in
Afghanistan in 1979 but no debate is set on this year's milder
document.
   Sharq is not a member of Afghanistan's governing Communist
Party, and the Soviet Union has indicated he could be a compromise
figure in a broad-based government.
   But diplomats at the U.N., speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Pakistan and the United States, which have supported the
rebels, find Sharq unacceptable because of his association with the
Afghan government headed by Najib.
   The Afghan Mission said Sharq would arrive Tuesday and meet with
U.N. officials. His schedule was not given but he is expected to
address the U.S. Council on Foreign Relations in a closed meeting,
although not the General Assembly.
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, chairman of a seven-member guerrilla
alliance, announced in Islamabad, Pakistan, that the rebels would
send a delegation to the United Nations. He reiterated that the
rebels want to form an anti-Marxist government in Afghanistan.
   For the first time in nine years the General Assembly will adopt
a resolution on Afghanistan by consensus _ not a divisive vote _
after the Soviet Union, Pakistan, Afghanistan and the United States
agreed on the document, diplomats said. Previous resolutions
denounced the Soviet military intervention and demanded the troops
withdraw.
   Action on the Afghan resolution is expected to be taken Thursday.
   Sharq recently told reporters in Kabul, the Afghan capital, that
both the governing party and rebels lack the trust of the people.
   The Soviet Union repeatedly has accused Pakistan of violating
the U.N.-mediated Afghanistan accords by continuing to arm and
train the rebels.
   The accords were signed last April 15 in Geneva by Afghanistan
and Pakistan with the United States and Soviet Union as guarantors.
The rebels did not take part but were represented by Pakistan.
   The Soviet Union intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979, and
at the time the accords were signed had more than 100,000 military
personnel there. The agreements provide for the complete withdrawal
of those troops by next Feb. 15. They also call for Pakistan not t
interference in Afghanistan's internal affairs.
   On Monday the 15-member Security Council adopted a resolution
confirming the formation of a 50-member U.N. observer force in
Afghanistan and Pakistan to monitor the Soviet troop withdrawal and
check for violations.
   Afghanistan and the Soviets have said the force is too small and
that it has failed to investigate complaints charging Pakistan with
violations of the accords.
</TEXT>
