<1ST_LINE>u p AM-HouseRaces 1stLd-Writethru a0679 10-31 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Races, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Once Again, House Incumbents Enjoying Huge Financial Advantages</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 final grafs with lists of highest spenders and money
raisers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House incumbents have a nearly 6-to-1 edge
over their opponents in fund raising, including a twelvefold
advantage in garnering contributions from special interest groups,
a private study showed Monday.
   The study by Common Cause, the advocacy organization that is a
frequent critic of electoral activities, illustrates one of the
major reasons that there has been little turnover in the House in
recent elections.
   Common Cause President Fred Wertheimer said the incumbents'
fund-raising edge is creating ``a challenger-proof House of
Representatives'' and added, ``The `people's body' established by
our founding fathers is starting to look like England's
life-tenured House of Lords.''
   Common Cause, compiling House candidates' campaign finance
reports from Jan. 1, 1987, through Sept. 30, 1988, found that
incumbents had raised $136.9 million to $25.3 million for
challengers during the period.
   That included a $62.4 million to $5.3 million margin in funds
contributed by PACs, the committees formed by companies, labor
unions and other special interest groups.
   Incumbents had not only outspent their opponents by $92 million
to $20.9 million, but they also had a dramatic $79.3 million to
$3.6 million advantage in cash on hand for the campaign's final
weeks.
   Of the 328 races in which a representative faces a major party
opponent on Election Day, incumbents had raised more money than
challengers in 323 cases; received more from PACs in 316 instances;
outspent their opponents in 315 contests and had more money left in
320 races.
   Democratic and Republican incumbents both enjoy mammoth
financial advantages over their challengers, although Democrats _
who control the House and thus have more political power _ have the
widest edge.
   On average, Democratic incumbents raised more money in PAC
contributions than GOP challengers by $166,783 to $4,724.
Republican House members accepted an average of $132,064 from PACs,
compared with $31,408 received from PACs by Democratic challengers.
   Of the 435 House seats, 408 incumbents are seeking re-election,
including 80 who face no general election opponent from a major
party.
   In 1986, 98 percent of the House members seeking new terms were
re-elected.
   Besides having an easier time raising money, incumbents often
represent congressional districts that were drawn to include large
numbers of party supporters and in which the lawmaker already has
name recognition. They also make use of the perks of their jobs,
including their staffs and their ability to introduce bills and
help constituents.
   The 10 House candidates who raised the most money through Sept.
30 are Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., $1,286,467; Rep. Joseph
Kennedy, D-Mass., $1.228,525; Rep. Joseph DioGuardi, R-N.Y.,
$1,222,688; Rep. Jim Moody, D-Wis., $1,146,656, and Tom Campbell,
GOP candidate in California's 12th District, $1,085,250.
   Also Gary K. Hart, Democratic challenger in California's 19th
District, $1,059,739; Rep. Robert Lagomarsino, R-Calif., Hart's
opponent, $941,819; Rep. Jim Courter, R-N.J., $897,265; Rep. Ronald
Dellums, D-Calif., $867,080; and Rep. Peter Kostmayer, D-Pa.,
$858,885.
   The 10 top spending House candidates are Dornan, $1,169,163;
Campbell, $1,020,663; Moody, $1,006,549; Lagomarsino, $964,325;
Hart, $896,407; Jerry Schenken, Republican candidate in Nebraska's
2nd District, $811,674; Christopher Cox, GOP candidate in the
California 40th District, $770,564; Kennedy, $761,652; Rep. Bob
McEwen, R-Ohio, $758,648; and DioGuardi, $751,083.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
