<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HammettUp 1stLd-Writethru a0758 10-31 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hammett Up, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writing Contest Winners Get What They Had Comin'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewords 4th graf to match wording from book.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were all there in spirit at John's
Grill: Sam Spade, Nick Charles and the Continental Op _ private
eyes in a public place, watching from the shadows Monday as
would-be writers played trick-or-treat with the ghost of novelist
Dashiell Hammett.
   The assignment was to ham-up Hammett, San Francisco's
hard-boiled gumshoe-turned-mystery writer who gave us such
treasures as ``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``The Thin Man,'' and ``The
Big Knockover.''
   About 100 hopefuls entered this ``bad writing'' contest, sending
in send-ups from Vermont, Illinois, Washington, Florida and
elsewhere. They all ended up at John's, a swell chop house in a
not-so-swell part of town.
   Hammett used to lap it up at the bar, but he would have had a
hard time swallowing the entries read on Monday. They were
definitely not the stuff dreams are made of.
   ``Nick was the thinnest man Nora'd ever seen. Handcuffs slipped
from his wrists up over his head to encircle his waist. He'd gotten
out of a lot of tight spots that way....
   ```Tell me the truth,''' Nora said. `When you were on the floor
wrestling with Mimi, did you have anorexia?''
   Oddly enough, that kind of prose was good enough to tie Kevin
Killian for first with William Vlach. Both men are San Franciscans,
both have real jobs and both want to be novelists.
   Killian got the nod for making an obscure pun. When ``The Thin
Man'' was first published in 1934, one line was deleted by censors.
Nora really asked Nick if he had ``an erection'' when he wrestled
with Mimi.
   Killian said his first novel is coming out soon.
   Vlach, a psychiatrist by trade, described a violent scene where
Brigid slams Babe McDougall on the back of his big head with a
two-by-four, leaving ``his right eye dangling out of it's socket
like'' something that can't be described in a family newspaper.
Vlach went on nicely:
   ``She turned to me, the Continental Cop, and said with a tear
dribbling through her eye liner like Moses parting the Red Sea,
`You won't turn me in. I love you. You love me.'
   ``I counted the lies in those three sentences, multiplied by
three, then opened the door for her pal, little Joel Egypt ... When
the cops got there I turned them both in. Her because she said she
loved me. Him because he called me Donald Dick.''
   OK, so these guys aren't going to get Pulitzers. The grand prize
package in this public relations gimmick was a bottle of cheap gin,
a ham sandwich and a hard-boiled egg. Vlach and Killian each got
their own, so they don't have to share, but it didn't keep them
from feeling like losers.
   ``I'm pretty disappointed,'' Killian griped. ``All I got was a
bottle of cheap gin and a moldy old ham sandwich.'' He apparently
forgot about the egg, and the free publicity.
   Nobody can say the judging wasn't fair, although somebody
probably will. The three panelists were: Hal Lipset, a real-life
detective who's cracked open more cases in 42 years than Hammett
could on a lost weekend; Don Herron, who has conducted walking
tours through ``Hammett's San Francisco'' for the past 12 years;
and Joe Gores, who wrote the novel ``Hammett'' that inspired the
1982 film of the same name.
</TEXT>
