<2ND_LINE>AM-Irate Passengers,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irate Passengers Take Over Three Domestic Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irate passengers briefly took over
three planes within a 24-hour period on Sunday and Monday to
protest flight cancellations due to bad weather and equipment, an
official of the nation's flag carrier said.
   Enrique Santos, Philippine Airlines vice president for public
relations, said in a telephone interview the incidents arose from
the airport situation at the central city of Bacolod, about 300
miles southeast of Manila.
   Santos said several flights to Bacolod had been canceled or
delayed since October because some equipment there had broken down
and would give incoming flights ``poor navigational aid.''
   He said the first of the three incidents occurred Sunday in
Manila when a domestic flight bound for Bacolod was canceled
because of the weather.
   Upon being informed of the cancellation, about 109 passengers
led by an unidentified lawyer took over a plane scheduled to leave
for Davao in the south and demanded to be flown to Bacolod, he said.
   The protesting passengers left the plane after 20 minutes, when
PAL authorities assured their booking for another flight Monday.
   Monday's flight left Manila without incident but upon landing at
Bacolod, the passengers refused to leave the plane and demanded
that the airport's radio and runway lights be repaired immediately.
   The passengers left the plane an hour later after local
officials assured them of action on their request, Santos said.
   On a return flight to Manila, six passengers refused to leave
their plane for an hour to protest what they deemed ``an apparent
discrimination'' against Bacolod airport. They left after being
told eight other domestic flights were canceled due to bad weather,
Santos said.
   Santos said PAL officials had not decided whether to file
charges against the passengers.
</TEXT>
