<HEAD>Kidnap Victim Released After More Than Four Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAGLIARI, Sardinia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman builder who was abducted 4{
months ago was released Monday night by kidnappers who earlier sent
a bloody piece of a human ear along with a demand for $2.5 million
ransom, authorities said.
   Giulio De Angelis, who suffers from a heart condition, was
released at about 8 p.m. (2 p.m. EST) Monday between Bolotana and
Illorai in the central part of this Italian island in the
Mediterranean. He was kidnapped June 12 from his villa on
Sardinia's exclusive Costa Smeralda.
   The Italian news agency AGI said De Angelis was taken to a
hospital in Alghero. It said he was weakened by his months of
imprisonment.
   Hospital officials and police refused to give any details on his
condition, however, and would not immediately say if the piece of
ear sent with the ransom note belonged to De Angelis, the agency
reported.
   Last August, authorities intercepted a package sent to De
Angelis' family which contained a 1{-inch piece of a human ear and
a note demanding, ``Four billion (lire, $2.5 million) or we'll
return him to you in little pieces.''
   ``Do it quickly, pay, they want to kill me,'' De Angelis wrote
in a note enclosed with the ear.
   AGI and ANSA, another Italian news agency, both quoted
unidentified sources as saying the family paid a ransom of $2.26
million for his release. They said the kidnappers originally
demanded $15.08 million.
