<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sand-to-Gold     10-31 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sand-to-Gold,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investors Nationwide Lost At Least $300 Million, Commission Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY GIBBS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oklahoma Securities Commission accused
a defunct brokerage firm Monday of using high-pressure, abusive
sales tactics to persuade thousands of people across the country to
invest in a scheme to turn sand into gold.
   The Securities Commission estimated losses from the scheme total
$300 million nationwide, and at least $4 million in Oklahoma.
   The commission is seeking to revoke the license of the Tulsa
firm of Fitzgerald, DeArman and Roberts and seven of its salesmen
and principals, said Susan Bryant, administrator of the Oklahoma
Department of Securities.
   The firm's offices have been closed since June, and liquidation
proceedings are under way by the Securities Investor Protection
Corp., a federal agency that insures investor funds in the event of
the failure of a brokerage firm.
   The commission accuses the brokerage firm and the salesmen of
using high-pressure, abusive sales tactics to promote stock in
GoldCor, a Florida company that claimed to have a secret process
for turning black, volcanic beach sand in Costa Rica into gold.
   Even though GoldCor had no gold or other real assets, the price
of its stock rose on the over-the-counter market from 3 to 6 cents
per share when the scheme began in 1986 to about $11 per share
before tumbling last February. It is presently at 3 to 9 cents a
share, Ms. Bryant said.
   The precipitous drop followed a critical article in the business
magazine Barron's, and a financial statement that showed GoldCor
had no revenues, Ms. Bryant said.
   ``The real question is, does this company have any real value at
all,'' she said at a state Capitol news conference.
   She said the $300 million in estimated losses was based on the
peak price of GoldCor stock before it began dropping in Feburary.
   ``Probably thousands of people nationwide were touched by it in
some way,'' said Ms. Bryant.
   She said the Securities Exchange Commission in Florida has filed
a civil lawsuit against GoldCor, but said she wasn't aware of any
other action involving the company.
   Up to 14 firms besides Fitzgerald, DeArman and Roberts were
selling GoldCor stock at one time, but ``these were the people who
seemed to be pushing it above and beyond what they should have
been,'' Ms. Bryant said.
   Ms. Bryant said the firm's salesmen promised investors GoldCor
stock would double or triple in price, suggesting they had insider
information.
   At least two of the 65 Oklahoma investors identified so far were
retired people who cleaned out their retirement accounts to invest
in GoldCor stock, Ms. Bryant said.
   ``These were people who lost money who didn't have it to lose,''
she said.
   The commission said individual losses in Oklahoma from the
GoldCor scheme ranged from $1,000 to $450,000.
   In addition to revoking licenses, the commission wants to bar
the seven individuals from further associating with securities
firms in the state.
   The commission action Monday amounted to a 15-day notice of its
intent to take administrative action.
   ``We'll review the case to see if there should be a referral for
criminal prosecution,'' Ms. Bryant said, adding that it is a felony
under Oklahoma law to trade securities using false information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
