<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Argentine-Falklands     10-31 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentine-Falklands,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Sentences Junta Members for Falklands War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian court stripped Gen.
Leopoldo Galtieri, the former military president, of his rank
Monday and sentenced him to 12 years in prison for mismanaging the
1982 Falklands war with Britain.
   In partial confirmation of an earlier ruling by the highest
military tribunal, the Federal Appeals Court gave the same sentence
to the other members of Galtieri's junta _ Adm. Jorge Isaac Anaya,
then navy commander, and Brig. Gen. Basilio Lami Dozo, who was
chief of the air force.
   The military tribunal's verdict automatically went for review to
the civilian appeals court, which can revise civilian or military
judicial rulings and even act as a court of first resort.
   Defense lawyers said the convictions probably will be appealed
to the Supreme Court.
   Judge Horacio Cattani, president of the four-member panel, said
all three officers were ``equally responsible'' for the ``mistakes,
omissions and negligence'' that led to defeat in the 74-day war
over the islands Argentina calls the Malvinas.
   Galtieri, Anaya and Lami Dozo constituted the third military
junta to rule after President Isabel Peron was deposed in March
1976.
   Appeals court judges acquitted three other officers who were
instrumental in carrying out the war _ Gens. Mario Benjamin
Menendez and Omar Parada, and Vice Adm. Juan Jose Lombardo, all now
retired.
   The case stems from the junta's decision to invade the South
Atlantic islands April 2, 1982, and the conduct of the war until
Menendez surrendered his troops on June 14 at Stanley, capital of
the Falklands.
   In May 1986, the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces convicted
Galtieri, Anaya and Lami Dozo of negligence and incompetence,
sentencing them to 12, 14 and 8 years in jail respectively and
stripping them of rank. Menendez, Parada, Lombardo and seven other
officers were acquitted.
   Cattani, president of the appeals panel, said sentences for the
three junta members were made identical because doing otherwise
risked ``inciting the protagonists, in the case of a similar
conflict, to act independently ... losing sight of the fact that
... only a joint action would make possible a victory.''
   Prosecutor Luis Moreno Ocampo alleged when the appeal began July
26 that the armed forces were ill-trained, poorly led, and acted
independently of each other.
   He focused on Anaya's decision to withdraw the navy from combat
after a British submarine sank the cruiser Belgrano in May 1982,
and the failure of Parada, who commanded army troops on the
islands, to establish a command post.
   Officers called by the prosecution testified Galtieri did not
believe Britain would fight to regain the islands or that the
United States would help the British.
   Galtieri, 62, claimed Argentina almost won the war and charges
of mismanagement were unfounded.
   In an emotional defense Oct. 17, he said, ``Would I do it again?
Given the same circumstances and conditions, would I proceed in the
same manner? The answer is yes. I, Lt. Gen. Galtieri would proceed
the same way as I did.''
   Argentina has claimed the islands since 1810, the year it
asserted independence from Spain. Britain has ruled them since 1833.
   The chilly, windswept archipelago is home to about 1,900
sheepherders and fishermen. Possession conveys rights to natural
resources, including abundant fishing fields and possible oil
deposits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
