<HEAD>Mexican President Meets with Fidel Castro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Miguel de la Madrid of Mexico met
Cuban President Fidel Castro on Monday in the first of two sessions
scheduled for his three-day visit to the island nation, the Cuban
news agency Prensa Latina said.
   The government agency gave no details of the talks.
   Thousands of Cubans greeted de la Madrid at the airport Monday
and Havana's streets were decorated with welcoming banners, the
dispatch, monitored in Mexico City, reported.
   Before sitting down with Castro, de la Madrid placed flowers at
a monument honoring Jose Marti, the 19th-century Cuban poet,
essayist and revolutionary patriot.
   Mexico has been one of communist Cuba's staunchest allies in the
hemisphere. The visit will be de la Madrid's last official trip
abroad before turning over the government to Carlos Salinas de
Gortari on Dec. 1.
   Increasing trade between the two countries is expected to be one
of the main topics of de la Madrid's discussions with Castro.
   Mexico has had a favorable trade balance with Cuba since 1983,
Prensa Latina said.
   The Mexico City newspaper El Nacional on Sunday quoted de la
Madrid as saying in Punta del Este, Uruguay:
   ``We hope that the future brings Cuba closer to the other Latin
American countries and that a solution to the sharp differences
this nation has with the United States will be found within the
framework of dignity and respect for the Cuban people and within
the principles of international law that we Latin Americans
support.''
   His comments followed a summit meeting last week with six other
Latin American leaders.
