<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Parties-Money 1stLd-Writethru a0760 10-31 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parties-Money, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Surpass Goal, But Not GOP In Raising Funds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with comparative 1984 figure SUBS 3rd graf; to
update with precise number on big donors SUBS 10th graf bgng,
`However the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democrats are touting record-breaking fund
raising for the 1988 election with $50 million, but they still
haven't caught up to the traditionally richer Republican party.
   The Republican National Committee and its state-based ``Victory
'88'' program have raised some $92 million, finance director Phil
Smith said Monday.
   The Democratic National Committee announced it has surpassed its
fund-raising goal of $50 million at $50.3 million, the most the
national party has ever raised for an election. In 1984, the party
raised $24 million, said spokeswoman Julie Anbender.
   Both parties have engaged in an all-out effort to raise
so-called soft money, which consists of contributions that would
not be allowed in the federal election process but can be used by
the parties for generic and state-related election activity that
ends up indirectly benefiting the presidential candidates.
   For candidates seeking election to the presidency or Congress,
the law limits individual contributions to $1,000 and bars
corporate and union funds, all of which can be accepted by the
parties themselves.
   In the general election, no private contributions are permitted
for presidential candidates because they receive $46 million from
the taxpayer-supported public fund to wage their campaigns.
   In addition, each national party can spend $8.3 million on its
presidential nominee.
   The parties are collecting millions on top of that.
   Robert Farmer, head of the Democratic Party's Victory Fund '88,
said the party's $50 million had come from 325,000 donors, with an
average contribution of $154.
   However, the party also received contributions of $100,000 or
more from 142 individuals, said Anbender.
   Direct mail brought in some $300,000 a day, for $18 million of
the $50 million total, the party said in a news release, while more
than 75 large fund-raising events brought in another $18 million.
   On the Republican side, more than 125 contributors gave $100,000
or more as part of the ``Team 100'' program, said Smith.
   The Republicans' ``Victory '88'' program, in which money goes
directly to state-level party organizations, has surpassed its goal
of $25 million, raising $27 million so far, Smith said.
   GOP nominee George Bush and his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle,
have helped that fund substantially by appearing several times a
week at high-ticket fund-raising events out on the campaign trail.
   Smith said RNC mail in the past two weeks has produced more than
$300,000 a day, with an average $25 contribution. He called it ``a
boom'' the likes of which he has not seen since 1980.
   ``It's been very easy,'' to raise money since August, he said,
contending that people are reacting out of fear of what they
foresee as bad economic conditions should Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis win the election.
</TEXT>
