<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Vandalism,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont Vandalism Incident Not the First</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vandalism of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' campaign
headquarters in Burlington, Vt., was not the first such incident, a
Dukakis national campaign spokesman said Monday.
   Dukakis spokesman Steven Akey said another incident involving a
campaign headquarters occurred in Tallahasee, Fla., when a big
Dukakis sign in front of the headquarters was torn down.
   In Vermont, vandals on Sunday broke into the building that
houses the Vermont presidential campaign offices of Dukakis, a
campaign representative said.
   Andre Oliver, the head of Dukakis' Vermont campaign, said that
while no attempts were made to break into the offices, 15 to 20
bumper stickers were plastered on walls in the hallways, saying
``Smart Democrats Vote Republican.'' Posters were also ripped off
the walls and cut in half.
   Akey also cited individual incidents of vandalism in the yards
of Dukakis supporters in Maine, Montana, California, Tennessee,
Arkansas and Texas.
   All the incidents have occurred within the last 10 days, Akey
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
