<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     10-31 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Delegation Reviews Haiti's Human Rights Situation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A U.S. congressional delegation met
Monday with officials of the military government to evaluate the
human rights situation and democratic reforms, linked to restoring
aid to Haiti.
   The six-member team arrived Sunday night for a five-day visit
that will include meetings with private citizens, organizations and
top members of the government of Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril who assumed
the presidency in a Sept. 17 coup.
   Washington suspended $70 million in aid to Haiti after
indiscriminate killings by thugs forced the cancellation of
elections on Nov. 29, 1987. Soldiers did not try to stop the
killers who shot or hacked to death at least 34 people at polling
booths.
   ``We are here to listen,'' said Steven Horblit, legislative
director for Rep. Walter E. Fauntroy, D-Washington D.C. ``We will
base our recommendation on what the attitude of Congress should be
on our asssesment of the general situation of Haiti.''
   Fauntroy, president of the Congressional Task Force on Haiti,
has indicated he is in favor of renewing aid. Haiti is the Western
Hemisphere's poorest nation.
   Horblit said the U.S. group hopes to meet with Avril but a
meeting has not been confirmed. He said the delegation would
discuss human rights, restoration of the 1987 constitution,
establishment of an independent electoral council and controls
against drug trafficking.
   Avril has pledged to set up an independent council to schedule
municipal and legislative elections. He said presidential elections
would take place only after local balloting and probably not before
2-2{ years.
   The military-dominated government of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy was
ousted and Avril installed in office by rebellious soldiers, who
demanded an end to state-sponsored violence and restoration of the
constituion suspended by Namphy in June.
   Namphy headed a junta that ruled Haiti after dictator
Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to France in February 1986 during
anti-government riots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
