<DOCNO> AP881031-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iceland-Dogs     10-31 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iceland-Dogs,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reykjavik Says No to Dogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Reykjavik, who did not
allow dogs from 1924 until an experiment began four years ago, have
decided to do without them again.
   In a week-long referendum that attracted 12.8 percent of the
eligible voters, 60.2 percent voted against continuing the
experiment. The results were announced Sunday night.
   Mayor David Oddsson, a dog owner, said people who have permits
for dogs will be allowed to keep them until the animals die.
   Dogs were banished from this city of 88,000 people in 1924 after
an outbreak of dog-related diseases.
   A compromise in 1984 set rules for the keeping of dogs during a
four-year experimental period, while leaving the ban on the statute
books.
   Under those rules, Reykjavik's 850 registered dog-owners pay
yearly license fees equivalent to $120, each dog must have an
annual medical checkup and owners must carry insurance.
   No dogs are allowed in the city's central district. They must
stay out of public parks between 8 a.m. and 9 p.m. and cannot enter
any public building, restaurant, playground, bus or barbershop.
Leashes are required at all times.
   Of the 68,570 eligible voters, 8,777 participated in the
referendum. The vote was 5,279 to ban dogs and 3,454 to continue
the 1984 program.
</TEXT>
