<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-31 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers Dampen Halloween Night in the South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms Monday put a damper on
trick-or-treating youngsters in the South, while parts of Michigan
and eastern Wisconsin got a dusting of light snow.
   Fog, low clouds and drizzle extended from the southern Plains
southward to the Gulf Coast as warm, moist air from the Gulf of
Mexico flowed over cool air. Showers and thunderstorms developed in
southeastern and south-central Texas, with winds gusting to 54 mph
at Alice and 44 mph at Corpus Christi and McAllen.
   Farther east, showers were scattered from the eastern Gulf Coast
to the southern Atlantic states, but rainfall generally was less
than half an inch.
   Light snow mixed with light rain dampened central upper Michigan
and eastern Wisconsin, and roads in the Upper Peninsula were icy
because of snow.
   Out West, fog and low clouds draped the northern Pacific coast.
   Temperatures across the country Monday afternoon ranged from the
30s in northern Minnesota, northern Wisconsin and Upper Michigan,
in the 40s in New England, the Appalachians, the lower Great Lakes
region, northern Plains and northern Rockies and up into the 70s in
northern Florida, southern Texas and Southern California, and in
the 80s in southern Florida and the desert Southwest. Elsewhere it
was in the 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 29
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 95 degrees at Palm Springs and
Thermal, Calif. The overnight low Monday was 12 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Rain was forecast Tuesday from the Atlantic coast westward to
the upper Ohio Valley, the lower Great Lakes and the Appalachians,
with thunderstorms expected in the South. Showers and thunderstorms
also will be scattered over Florida and southeastern Alabama. Snow
showers again were predicted for Upper Michigan, and rain was
expected across the Pacific Northwest and Northern California.
   Temperatures were expected in the 30s again in upper Michigan
and in the 40s and 50s from the Plains and the upper Mississippi
Valley across the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley and the Appalachians
to the middle and northern Atlantic coast and in Washington state
and northern Idaho. Temperatures were forecast in the 60s and 70s
elsewhere, but in the 80s in southern Florida, southern Texas and
the southern Rockies and between 85 and 95 degrees in the desert
Southwest and inland valleys of Southern California.
</TEXT>
