<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WellsFargo     10-31 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wells Fargo,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Sentenced for Conspiracy in Wells Fargo Robbery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Berrios Berrios is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who admitted plotting a toy
giveaway with some of the $7.1 million stolen from Wells Fargo in
1983 was sentenced Monday to five years in prison.
   Luz Berrios Berrios, 38, an occupational therapist from Puerto
Rico, received the maximum prison term, but was spared a $10,000
fine for her guilty plea in September to a charge of conspiracy to
transport stolen money.
   U.S. District Judge T. Emmet Clarie said a fine would be
pointless because ``this lady is indigent for all intents and
purposes.''
   Her attorney, Jacob Wieselman, asked that Berrios be sent to the
federal minimum security prison in Danbury, noting that she is just
a few weeks pregnant and needs to be near her family.
   But Clarie said that because Berrios is pregnant, the best
prison for her would be in Lexington, Ky. The judge, however, said
he would let Wieselman see if arrangements could be made at Danbury.
   On the day a jury was to be picked for her trial, Berrios
admitted to conspiring with others in Puerto Rico to send between
$5,000 and $12,000 to Hartford to pay for toys given away on Jan.
6, 1985, Three Kings Day, the day when people in many Latin
American countries traditionally exchange gifts.
   She said she presumed the money was from that stolen on Sept.
12, 1983, from the Wells Fargo depot in West Hartford in the second
largest cash heist in U.S. history.
   The government contends that Berrios is a leader of Los
Macheteros, a terrorist group seeking Puerto Rican independence.
The group has claimed a role in attacks on U.S. installations in
Puerto Rico.
   Berrios' husband, Juan E. Segarra Palmer, who prosecutors say is
a key defendant in the Wells Fargo robbery, and four other men are
now on trial before Clarie.
   Nine others are awaiting trial on charges in the robbery. One
other defendant has pleaded guilty.
</TEXT>
