<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0720 10-31 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Ridicules Dukakis For Using Liberal Label, Rejects Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 19th graf pvs, bgng, `Kentucky, where,'
with Bush comment from appearance in Kansas City, Mo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush mocked Michael Dukakis
on Monday for claiming the liberal label that the Democratic
nominee had long avoided, and ridiculed Dukakis' invitation for a
third televised debate on election eve next week.
   Instead, Bush suggested that Dukakis debate himself, ``the New
Left vs. the Old Left.''
   ``Dukakis vs. Dukakis ... it should be an entertaining debate,''
the vice president said in rallies in St. Louis and Louisville, Ky.
   Bush said the Dukakis who now calls himself a liberal could
debate the earlier one who shunned the ``L word,'' which Bush and
President Reagan have used repeatedly to taunt the Massachusetts
governor.
   Faced with an apparent narrowing of his lead over Dukakis in
several major states, Bush appealed for the support of disenchanted
Democrats. He borrowed a phrase made popular by former President
Nixon in calling them ``the silent majority.''
   As the presidential campaign entered its final week, the GOP
nominee wasted no time in poking fun at his Democratic rival for
embracing liberalism Sunday during a campaign tour of California on
Sunday, and dismissed Dukakis' challenge to join him in an
hour-long debate the night before the Nov. 8 election.
   ``An election eve debate? Read my hand gesture. That says it,''
Bush told reporters accompanying him on Air Force Two in a
paraphrase of his ``read my lips: no new taxes'' line.
   The vice president held up one finger, then two, to indicate the
two previous presidential debates in Winston-Salem, N.C., and Los
Angeles in late September and mid-October.
   Speaking to a rally in the Commonwealth Civic Center in
Louisville, Bush asked his audience to ``remember how (Dukakis)
jumped all over me for using the L-word'' in their second debate.
   ``Well, yesterday, miracle of miracles. Headlines. Read all
about it. He's using the liberal label again,'' Bush said.
   Suggesting that Dukakis debate himself, the GOP nominee said:
   ``One could claim to be on the side of ordinary Americans and
the other could explain whether he thinks ordinary Americans oppose
the death penalty for drug kingpins like he does, favor weekend
furloughs for convicted murders ... oppose asking for a requirement
for teachers to lead the kids in the Pledge of Allegiance.''
   He repeated those lines at a subsequent rally in the remodeled
Union Station in St. Louis, adding that ``at the end, the moderator
should say, will the real governor of Massachusetts stand up.''
   Bush boarded a train for a five-minute ride into the cavernous,
open-air station, where he addressed several thousand people from a
platform he shared with an oversized pumpkin with ``Bush-Quayle
88'' carved in its side.
   ``We're in a horserace,'' Bush told the crowd. ``I won't settle
for anything less than a first-place finish.''
   In Louisville, Bush said he could now use the ``L word freely,''
and declared that ``we cannot let the naive disarmers and the
nuclear freezers back into the White House.''
   In his appeal to what he called ``abandoned'' Democrats, Bush
said the Democratic Party had moved away from mainstream America.
   ``So, my pitch here, in the last eight days, is to those good
Democrats, the rank and file,'' he said. ``I tell them: have hope,
have confidence.''
   Kentucky, where local polls show Bush enjoys a double-digit
lead, has nine electoral votes. Missouri, where polls show the race
to be much closer, has 11 electoral votes.
   At another pep rally in Kansas City, Mo., Bush said told the
crowd, ``we are involved in a tough race,'' and repeated his pledge
to campaign as if the Republican ticket were 10 points behind in
the polls.
   ``I don't care what these polls show,'' he said.
   The vice president planned to spend most of the week campaigning
in large Midwestern industrial states before heading for California.
   Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager, said the vice president
planned to spend much of his remaining time in Dukakis'
``must-win'' states.
   ``If you and your opponent are in his base states, then that's a
sign you've met your goals and he hasn't,'' Atwater said in an
interview.
   He said Bush running mate Dan Quayle would continue to campaign
``in our base states.''
   Meanwhile, the Bush campaign distributed a 348-page compilation
of the vice president's campaign speeches bearing the title
``Leadership on the Issues,'' in an apparent effort to blunt
criticism of negative GOP campaign advertising attacking Dukakis.
   Bush stood by a stack of the books at the St. Louis rally and
said, ``This is what the campaign is about, not those TV ads.''
   At least one of the Bush speeches reprinted in the book had been
sanitized. The vice president's highly publicized misstatement
about Pearl Harbor Day occurring on Sept. 7 instead of Dec. 7
during a speech before the American Legion in Louisville does not
appear in the book's version of the speech.
</TEXT>
