<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0699 10-31 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Courts Women, Youths; Says He Smells Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP seven grafs new with Cerritos appearance, ads.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic underdog Michael Dukakis made
a populist pitch for the support of women and young voters Monday,
and said his boisterous reception ``smells like victory'' in the
Nov. 8 election.
   He won cheers from an audience at San Jose State College for
stands on abortion, the environment and economic opportunity, and
drew loud, approving boos when he lambasted Republican rival George
Bush and his running mate, Dan Quayle, on the same issues.
   But Dukakis refrained from using the word ``liberal'' until a
later appearance at Cerritos Community College in Los Angeles,
where he cloaked himself in the ``liberal tradition of great
presidents like Franklin Roosevelt and Harry Truman and John
Kennedy.''
   Dukakis started using the word Sunday in California, defiantly
proclaiming himself a liberal. Bush had repeatedly taunted Dukakis
with the ``L word'' during the fall campaign, saying the Democrat
has tried to hide his leftward leanings.
   Dukakis aides also released a text of a five-minute commercial
to be broadcast Tuesday night on NBC. In it Dukakis refers to
Roosevelt, Truman and Kennedy as well as Lyndon Johnson.
   ``This election has always been an uphill fight,'' Dukakis says
in the ad. ``But about some things, I'm as stubborn as my critics
say, and I'm determined that in the intense days of this last week
we will continue to see the truth and to speak it.''
   He also criticizes the tone of the Republican campaign, saying,
``They are running for the highest office in the land by waging the
lowest-level campaign in modern history.''
   At the San Jose appearance, he invoked the names of those three
presidents as having provided ``a caring government and caring
political leadership.'' Said Dukakis: ``That's the kind of
president I want to be.''
   ``It's Halloween today, isn't it?'' the Democratic nominee
reminded his noisy campus audience in this environmentally
sensitive state with its bigger-than-any prize of 47 electoral
votes.
   ``Mr. Bush is going to be passing himself as an
environmentalist. No treat for us. That's the biggest trick in the
book,'' Dukakis said.
   He reaffirmed his opposition to oil drilling off the California
coast and said the Reagan-Bush administration had ``the worst
environmental record in the history of this country.''
   He went on the counterattack against Bush's criticism of
pollution in Boston Harbor.
   ``I'm not the guy who polluted Boston Harbor,'' Dukakis said.
``I'm the guy who's cleaning it up, no thanks to Mr. Bush and his
friends.''
   Making his first major appeal to women voters, a traditional
source of Democratic strength, Dukakis said the Republican ticket
had ``been on the wrong side of every issue of special importance
to American women.''
   He said that if voters believe in comparable wages for both
sexes, affordable child care and parental leave laws, ``then we're
on your side.'' Dukakis then dropped his voice when he spoke of
abortion.
   Dukakis shook his head when he said Quayle had told a
12-year-old girl last week that if she were raped by her father and
became pregnant, ``the government had a right to force her to bear
that child.''
   The overflow San Jose audience of several hundred people erupted
in loud boos.
   (Quayle made no mention of the government when he answered an
11-year-old girl's question in Illinois last week about his advice
in such a situation. Quayle responded that he favored childbirth
over abortion even under those circumstances.)
   Dukakis said his Republican opponent wanted to outlaw abortions.
``I believe a choice that personal must be made by the woman in the
exercise of her beliefs,'' Dukakis said.
   He turned to his student listeners and quoted Kennedy's words
during a 1960 campaign visit to California. ``You have to decide
which candidate reflects your judgment of our country, of its needs
and of its future,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis boasted that he was narrowing Bush's once-formidable
lead in the polls and said: ``There is a feeling in the air and it
smells like victory to me.''
   He challenged the vice president again to join him in an
hour-long, nationally broadcast debate on election eve next Monday
night.
   ``You can't inherit the White House,'' Dukakis said. ``You've
got to earn the right to be president of the United States.''
   Bush dismissed the invitation during a campaign appearance in
Louisville, Ky., mockingly suggesting that Dukakis debate himself
in a matchup of ``the New Left vs. the Old Left.''
   Dukakis headed for Los Angeles and Ohio, a Midwestern industrial
state where the Democratic nominee also hopes to overtake Bush by
election night.
</TEXT>
