<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Banker     10-31 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Banker,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek-American Banker Barred From Leaving Greece</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judicial authorities on Monday forbid
Greek-American banker George Koskotas from leaving Greece while he
is under investigation following his indictment on charges of
forgery and embezzlement.
   Several newspapers have claimed that members of the governing
Panhellenic Socialist Movement, known as PASOK, have financial
links with Koskotas through his ownership of the Bank of Crete.
   The government promised full backing of the investigation.
Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said, ``We won't pardon
anyone, whether he belongs to PASOK or not.''
   Koskotas, 34, bought the Bank of Crete in 1984 and then built a
banking and publishing empire that controls three daily newspapers,
a radio station and the soccer team Olympiakos of Piraeus.
   He did not appear before the judicial council considering the
travel ban but issued a statement through his lawyer saying it was
unnecessary because he ``intends to remain in Greece at the
disposal of the authorities.''
   Koskotas was suspended earlier this month as chairman of the
Bank of Crete and was indicted on five counts of forgery and
embezzlement, mostly involving foreign exchange.
   The Bank of Greece, the country's central bank, has guaranteed
the equivalent of $80 million in private depositors' accounts at
the Bank of Crete.
   Koskotas also was sued Monday by Premier Andreas Papandreou's
36-year-old son, George, and two other senior officials in the
socialist government. They accused Koskotas of forgery and
defamation.
   George Papandreou, the education minister, said a document
purporting to show transfers totalling $5.3 million to the three
plaintiffs was a forgery.
   According to the document, a statement attributed to the
American brokerage firm Merrill Lynch & Co., transfers were made in
December 1987 of $2.3 million to George Papandreou, $500,000 to
National Economy Undersecretary George Petsos and $2.5 million to
Antonis Livanis, the premier's private secretary.
   George Papandreou showed reporters copies of the statement and a
letter from a New York lawyer's office saying Merrill Lynch & Co.
had no record of the transfers.
   The premier defended his son, saying ``the education minister
spoke the truth and the whole truth according to what we know.''
   Koskotas on Saturday resigned as chairman of his media group,
Grammi, saying he wanted to defend his ``personal honor in a way
that will not harm anyone at Grammi.''
   Haris Bousbourelis, a political editor, became chairman of the
group that publishes five magazines, three daily newspapers and
controls the SKY-100 radio station.
   Koskotas grew up in the United States, returned to Greece in
1979 and joined the Bank of Crete as an accountant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
