<HEAD>Syrian Soldier, Lebanese Policeman Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said a Syrian soldier and a
Lebanese policeman were wounded Monday in a gunfire attack on a
checkpoint manned by both police and troops.
   They said the raid by unidentified gunmen occurred near the
Hussein Bin Ali Vocational center in south Beirut's Bir el-Abed
district, which is controlled by the pro-Iranian fundamentalist
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Syrian troops were deployed in the Shiite slums last May to put
an end to a three-week bloodbath between Hezbollah and its
Syrian-backed archrival, Amal.
   In New York, U.N. officials announced Monday that
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar ordered an envoy,
Jean-Caude Aime, to assess the situation in Lebanon and meet with
political leaders.
   Aime, a U.N. director for special political affairs, was already
in Lebanon to study developments and report back to the
secretary-general.
   The secretary-general's spokeswoman, Nadia Younes, told
reporters the United Nations has many activities in Lebanon,
ranging from peacekeeping to humanitarian aid. She declined to
elaborate on Aime's purpose or disclose his schedule of meetings.
   Lebanon has endured 13{ years of civil war.
   The United Nations maintains that the troubles in Lebanon are an
internal problem, with international repercussions, she said.
