<2ND_LINE>AM-Yalies-Bush,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Yalies Against Bush' Rally Disrupted By Bush Backers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rally Monday on the Yale campus by a
group of students, alumni and faculty calling themselves ``Yalies
Against Bush'' was disrupted by a spirited contingent of Bush
backers who swarmed around speakers who took turns attacking the
vice president.
   As students carrying Bush-Quayle signs worked their way to the
front of the crowd, supporters of Michael Dukakis responded in
kind, crowding closer and closer to the speakers until they were
completely surrounded.
   Yale police attempted in vain to get the competing camps to pull
back.
   About 200 people attended the rally, and the proximity of the
crowd to the speakers made it difficult to hear the speeches from
any distance.
   The Bush supporters occasionally heckled but did not prevent
members of ``Yalies Against Bush,'' or John Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential candidate's son, from delivering their speeches.
   When speakers finished their remarks and ``Yalies Against Bush''
responded with ``Go Duke'' and other chants, the Bush supporters,
some of whom remained at the back of the crowd, yelled ``Four more
years.''
</TEXT>
