<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Turkey 2ndLd-Writethru a0768 10-31 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Turkey, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0768,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Warn Against Visit by Waldheim</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf pvs bgng, `Several members,'
to UPDATE with Waldheim arriving in Kuwait, likely topics of
discussion</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress have told the president of
Turkey that a meeting with Austrian President Kurt Waldheim would
damage Turkish ties with the United States.
   At the same time, a Turkish official said his government asked
Waldheim to stop in Istanbul rather than in Ankara, the capital, so
as not to make his visit appear official.
   Waldheim had asked to stop in Ankara and see President Kenan
Evren on his way home from the Middle East, said the official, who
declined to be named. But Turkish authorities informed Waldheim
that Evren would not be in Ankara that day and asked the Austrian
to stop in Istanbul instead.
   ``That way it doesn't seem like an official visit,'' he said.
   In a telegram to President Evren, six members of the House
subcommittee on Europe and the Middle East said they were
``appalled and shocked at the news that Kurt Waldheim will be
received by you early in November.''
   Waldheim, who has been shunned by Western governments because of
accusations that he facilitated Nazi war crimes in World War II, is
scheduled to stop in Turkey on Wednesday en route home from a
Middle East visit.
   ``The American people and the American Congress have expressed
their view of Waldheim by banning him from even visiting the United
States,'' the telegram said.
   ``We wish to see Turkish-U.S. relations strengthened, and
receiving Waldheim would have a very negative effect,'' the
lawmakers said. The six representatives were: Tom Lantos, D-Calif.,
Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., Lawrence Smith, D-Fla., Mel Levine,
D-Calif., Edward Feighan, D-Ohio, and Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y.
   Their subcommittee, headed by Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind.,
oversees the administration's policy toward Turkey and recommends
to Congress the amount of aid the NATO ally receives each year.
   Despite intense State Department efforts, aid for Turkey has
been reduced steadily by Congress in recent years. The
administration asked for $914.9 million for Turkey in fiscal year
1988, but only got $525.3 million.
   Several members of the Senate, including Rudy Boschwitz,
R-Minn., and Carl Levin, D-Mich., sent cables and letters to
Turkish Ambassador Sukru Elekdag urging his government to
reconsider its hosting of Waldheim.
   Meanwhile, Waldheim was greeted Monday in Kuwait with a red
carpet welcome and 21-gun salute at the start of his three-day
state visit. He had just completed a four-day visit to Syria.
   The topics for discussion in Kuwait were expected to be the same
as those in Syria: the Middle East peace process; the situation in
the Persian Gulf since Iran and Iraq stopped fighting; bilateral
relations and key international issues, officials said.
   The Justice Department last year placed Waldheim on a list of
people banned from the United States after reviewing evidence that
linked him with Nazi atrocities when he served as an officer in the
German army occupying the Balkans.
   In Ankara, the Foreign Ministry described Waldheim's visit as an
``unofficial stopover.'' Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz will greet
Waldheim at the airport in Istanbul and Evren will host a luncheon
for him later in the day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
