<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2028EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-TimesMirrorPoll 2ndLd-Writethru a0790 10-31 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Times Mirror Poll, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0790,890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST, TIME set by sources.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Polls Find Dukakis Rated Better on Crime but Hamstrung in Own
Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS graf on Wisconsin poll.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' counterattacks have improved
his rating as a crimefighter, but the Democratic presidential
nominee still suffers from unsteady support within his own party,
polls said Monday.
   Republican George Bush led by 11 points among likely voters in a
national survey by the Gallup Organization for the Times Mirror
Corp., 52 percent 41 percent, and by seven points, 52 percent 45
percent, in a poll by Louis Harris and Associates.
   The Times Mirror poll was done in the first half of last week;
the Harris poll was more recent, conducted Friday through Sunday.
Its 52-45 result was a very slight narrowing from 53-44 in a Harris
poll conducted Oct. 14-17.
   Dukakis only recently began to counter Bush's charges that he
was weak on crime, and the Harris poll indicated some results:
Fifty-three percent rated Dukakis soft on crime, still high but
down from 63 percent in the earlier poll.
   Harris also indicated that Dukakis had scored slightly by
portraying Bush's campaign advertisements as unfair. Seventy-five
percent called Bush's ads too negative, while 68 percent said the
same of Dukakis' ads.
   The Times Mirror poll, meanwhile, found support for Dukakis
uneven within his own party, while Bush marshalled monolithic
backing from Republicans and siphoned away some Democrats.
   Gallup said the presidential race has been largely stable for
months, with Bush ahead at least since September. But its poll
found an underlying factor in his favor: His supporters were more
loyal than they had been previously.
   Dukakis, meanwhile, has suffered slow erosion in his popularity,
to a point now lower than other candidates in recent years, the
poll said. And he lost support in some Democratic groups even while
gaining it in others.
   Bush's lead was based upon overwhelming support from
Republicans, solid backing from Republican-leaning independents and
``substantial defections'' from some Democratic groups, according
to Gallup's analysis of the results.
   ``For Dukakis, on the other hand, his support is not as strong
among his own partisans; and he is receiving virtually no
defections from members of core Republican groups,'' the analysis
said.
   The survey did find some room for change. Swing voters, those
who were undecided or said they might change their minds, made up
27 percent of the likely voters. And only about half of each
candidates' supporters backed them strongly.
   The problem in analyzing the race was Bush's stable lead on one
hand versus the softness of both candidates' support on the other.
``If Dukakis and the Dukakis campaign can get their act together
and speak to their constituencies or potential constituencies, they
can win it on the basis of the numbers,'' said Andrew Kohut,
Gallup's president. ``But that's a big if, given the course of the
campaign so far.''
   The Times Mirror poll divides the electorate into 10 evenly
sized groups whose members share general values. Its ``partisan
poor,'' for example, is a Democratic group; its ``enterprisers''
and ``moralists'' are Republican.
   Bush attracted 21 percent of the ``partisan poor,'' in the new
survey, significantly poaching in a Democratic stronghold. Dukakis,
by contrast, drew only 2 percent of the ``enterprisers'' and 3
percent of the ``moralists.''
   The last Times-Mirror poll, in September, identified
``disaffected'' voters, set apart by their suspicion of government,
as a swing group. After a nearly even division in May, they backed
Bush by 61-27 percent last month.
   In the new survey that preference held steady, and Bush's
supporters in the group grew more loyal to him: Fifty-one percent
said they were unlikely t switch to Dukakis, up from 36 percent
last month.
   ``In contrast, on the Democratic side, defections to George Bush
have doubled among `seculars' and significantly increased among the
`partisan poor,''' Gallup said. While Dukakis offset the losses
with gains in other Democratic groups, it said, the movement was
``indicative of the problems that the Dukakis campaign has had in
achieving enthusiastic support'' from some groups within his own
party.
   Additionally, among all registered voters, not just those likely
to vote, Dukakis was rated favorably by 48 percent, compared with
58 percent favorable for Bush. The poll analysis said Dukakis'
rating was ``significantly below'' those of most candidates in
recent presidential elections.
   The Times Mirror poll was conducted Oct. 23-26 among 2,006
registered voters, of whom 1,505 were considered likely to vote.
The error margin for the likely voter group was plus or minus three
points. The Harris poll was done among 1,250 likely voters and also
had a three-point margin of error.
   In a state poll Monday, ABC News put the race in California at
51 percent for Bush to 44 percent for Dukakis. That survey was done
Saturday and Sunday among 510 likely voters; while the spread was
within its margin of error of five points, other recent polls also
have found Bush slightly ahead there.
   In a separate poll in Missouri, Bush led Dukakis 53 percent to
39 percent among 397 likely voters. The poll was taken last Monday
through Thursday and had a margin of error of four points.
   In Wisconsin, a survey of 1,019 likely voters Sunday through
Thursday found Bush leading 45-40. The survey had a margin of error
of three points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
