<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Florence     10-31 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Florence,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florentines Vote To Limit Traffic in Historic City Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florentine voters overwhelmingly approved
in a non-binding referendum a plan to limit traffic in the city's
historic center, election results showed Monday.
   Returns from Saturday's poll indicated about 72 percent of the
voters favored an immediate and complete closure of the center to
private automobiles.
   The city said 154,120 people, about 43 percent of Florence's
354,730 registered voters, cast ballots.
   Voters indicated they want traffic closed completely to private
cars in an area bounded by the Arno River and Viale di
Circonvallazione, the street that circles the center. Florence
already has some restrictions on traffic there.
   The referendum does not require the city council to act. It was
designed to demonstrate to the city government voters' feelings on
the measure.
   Rome also is weighing further restrictions on its own city
center traffic because of pollution and congestion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
