<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Soldier,0123</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier Jailed For Belonging To Hostile Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslav military tribunal
convicted an ethnic Albanian soldier of belonging to a hostile
separatist organization and sentenced him to five years in jail
Monday, the Tanjug news agency reported.
   It said Pvt. Ismail Rasiti, 20, admitted at a court-martial in
Sarajevo, central Yugoslavia, that he organized an ethnic Albanian
nationalist group called the ``Burning Torch'' at a nearby garrison
last June.
   The ethnic Albanian minority, centered mostly in southern Kosovo
province, makes up about 9 percent of Yugoslavia's population of 23
million.
   Thousands of ethnic Albanians have been arrested since bloody
riots shook Kosovo in 1981, during a drive to obtain more autonomy
for the province.
</TEXT>
