<DOCNO> AP881031-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Lottomania 1stLd-Writethru a0749 10-31 0839</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lottomania, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,0862</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Clubs, Lone Player Officially Declared Winners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd to UPDATE with distribution of
funds, quotes from winners; picks up 4th graf pvs, `The
overall...'; INSERTS 3 grafs after 14th pvs, `Carrie Dragon...' to
UPDATE with more quotes; picks up 15th graf pvs, `Bill McKell...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gambling clubs and a lone player
will share a $61.98 million lottery jackpot that officials say is
the world's largest, it was announced Monday.
   The windfall will be divided among a group of 25 Sears employees
in Sacramento, 15 hospital workers in San Diego County, and Ron
Smith, a 45-year-old Shell Oil Co. production supervisor who lives
in Westminster, said lottery spokesman Bob Taylor.
   Each of the groups and Smith will receive one-third of the
jackpot, or nearly $20.66 million, which will be paid over two
decades in equal annual payments after taxes, Taylor said. The
lottery deducts 20 percent of winnings for federal income taxes.
   Officials said the Sears workers will get an estimated $33,000
annually after taxes for 20 years; the hospital workers, $55,000
each year for two decades after taxes; and Smith, $826,400 annually
after taxes for 20 years.
   Most of the 15 workers from the hospital in Fallbrook arrived at
a lottery district office in San Diego riding in limousines to
present their winning ticket.
   At Fallbrook Hospital, respiratory therapist and winner Jeff
Wilson declared, ``I'm about the only working millionaire at this
place today. Everybody else is off.''
   The overall jackpot increased from an estimated $60.8 million to
$61.98 million when annuities that will be used to make payments to
winners were purchased Monday, said Taylor.
   ``We're very common, real people,'' said Smith's wife, Linda.
``We have our friends and this is our house. We're not going to
move.''
   The two now earn about $40,000 a year. Smith said he plans to
quit his job so he and his wife can travel.
   Smith said he went to work Sunday and told co-workers of his
good fortune. ``They thought I was kidding,'' he said. ``Then they
decided I was serious.''
   Appliance repairman Frank T. Kopita, 42, of the El Dorado County
town of Shingle Springs, 30 miles east of Sacramento, held the
winning ticket for the group of Sears workers, lottery officials
said.
   The lottery first scheduled, then canceled a news conference
with the Sacramento winners. The employees said they wanted to
avoid the publicity and had to return to work, said lottery
spokeswoman Kim Rendahl.
   A woman who identified herself only as Shirley at the Sears
service center said she was one of 25 people in the pool there who
won. ``I'm pretty excited about it. Wouldn't anybody be?'' she said.
   Surinder Sanghera, owner of Sangheras House of Liquors in
Sacramento, where the Sears group bought its tickets, said of its
members: ``They are regulars. I think they've been buying here
since the lotto began.''
   Colleen M. Peach-Van Horn, a 36-year-old intensive care nurse,
held the winning ticket for 15 Fallbrook Hospital workers in San
Diego County.
   Carrie Dragon, a technician at the hospital, said she joined 13
nurses, laboratory technicians and other employees _ as well as a
friend of one of the workers _ in putting $40 each toward the
tickets. All told, she said, the group bought $600 worth of tickets.
   Wilson, another of the hospital winners, said he really hadn't
had much of a chance yet to celebrate.
   ``Monday mornings are busy around this place anyway,'' he said.
``Betwixt and between seeing my patients, I've had many
congratulations.''
   Asked what he planned to do with the money, Wilson said, ``I'd
like to pay my son's tuition (at University of California, Davis)
and maybe take a little vacation.''
   Bill McKeel, manager at the Circle K store where the group
bought tickets, said that half an hour after the drawing one member
of the group walked in to pick up the computer printout of winning
numbers.
   ``He got it, kissed it and started walking back out to his
truck, but before he could leave he had to sit down on the curb to
collect himself,'' McKeel said.
   The members of both winning groups will be responsible for
making their own arrangements to divide the money. The lottery pays
out to a single winner, the person holding the ticket.
   The jackpot was the world's largest lottery prize, Taylor said.
   The previous record was $56 million in Spain's El Gordo lottery
in 1983. The previous North American record was a $55.16 million
jackpot in Florida lotto last month, but that prize went to a
single winner.
   The winning numbers that produced the windfalls for 41 players
in Saturday night's ``Lotto 6@49'' drawing were: 5, 20, 26, 28, 32,
and 39.
   The jackpot soared because for the fourth consecutive time
nobody picked the six winning numbers between 1 and 49 in
Wednesday's $33.4 million drawing. The jackpot rolled over to the
Saturday game and grew with each ticket sale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
