<HEAD>Lawyer Slain by Gunmen Wearing Army Uniforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A lawyer who specialized in
land-dispute cases was stopped on a road and killed by two gunmen
wearing army uniforms, radio Haiti Inter reported Monday.
   It identified the victim as Jacques Phillipe, in his 30s, and
said one of two men traveling with the lawyer also may have been
killed.
   It did not identify the two companions but attributed its report
to the one known survivor.
   According to the broadcast, Phillippe and his friends were
driving back to Port-au-Prince from the town of St. Marc, 59 miles
north of the capital, when their car was stopped by two gunmen in
uniforms who forced their way into the vehicle.
   About six miles north of Port-au-Prince Philippe was told to
stop the car and his two companions were told to ``take to their
heels,'' the radio said.
   After shooting Phillipe the killers chased the two other men.
The survivor said he believed the other victim was shot to death in
a nearby canefield. The survivor made it safely to the army post of
Bon Ripos.
   Armed gangs committing crimes in and around Port-au-Prince are
believed to be former members of the disbanded Tonton Macoutes, the
private army of dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier who fled to France in
February 1986 during anti-government violence.
</TEXT>
