<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Carlucci     10-31 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Carlucci,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Arrives in Cairo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Abdel-Halim Abu-Ghazala
welcomed Frank C. Carlucci at Cairo International Airport on Monday
upon the U.S. defense secretary's arrival for a two-day official
visit.
   Carlucci flew in from Jordan and will go to Israel on Wednesday,
the final stop on his three-nation Middle East tour.
   He meets separately Tuesday with President Hosni Mubarak and
Abu-Ghazala, focusing on U.S.-Egyptian military cooperation and
Middle East problems.
   Abu-Ghazala told reporters hours before Carlucci landed that the
visit ``is in the context of the good relationship between the two
countries. Relations between the armed forces in the two countries
are very good.''
   Since 1980, Egypt has been the second largest recipient of U.S.
military aid after Israel. The aid to Cairo averages $1.3 billion
annually and has been comprised of outright grants since 1984.
   On a visit to Washington last March, Abu-Ghazala signed a
10-year memorandum of understanding with Carlucci, giving Egypt
special status as a strategic ally outside the framework of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Only Israel, Sweden and
Australia have similar accords with the United States.
   Abu-Ghazala said Monday that among topics he and Carlucci will
discuss is coproduction of the U.S.-designed M-1A1 Abrams tank.
   The Pentagon has valued the deal at $2 billion. It said the
transaction involves sale of 555 M-1A1s and that as many as 545 of
them could be built on a new assembly line in Egypt.
</TEXT>
