<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Wallenberg     10-31 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Wallenberg,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sweden To Press Moscow on Wallenberg Mystery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson said
Monday that Sweden will approach the Soviet Union again in an
attempt to obtain ``absolute clarity'' about the fate of Raoul
Wallenberg.
   Wallenberg, a Swedish diplomat, saved tens of thousands of
people from Nazi death camps and was arrested by Soviet forces in
Hungary at the end of World War II. Moscow said he died in a Soviet
prison in 1947, but Soviet dissident sources said he was seen in
the 1980s.
   Carlsson told a Swedish national television reporter that ``it
is our hope that with the new (Soviet) leadership we will get
absolute clarity in the Raoul Wallenberg case.''
   He indicated that Sweden will raise the issue at its next
high-level meeting with the Soviet Union.
   Wallenberg would be 76 years old if he is still alive.
</TEXT>
