<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Guerrillas 2ndLd-Writethru a0816 10-31 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Guerrillas, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0816,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Meet Church Leaders, Panamanian Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs `Salvadoran church ...' CORRECTING date of
last rebel-govt meeting to Oct. 27, 1987, sted last Oct. PICKS up
10th pvs: Gonzalez said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church leader gave Salvadoran
rebels a report Monday on proposals for a negotiated solution to
their 9-year-old war with U.S.-backed governments of El Salvador.
   Arturo Rivera Damas, Roman Catholic archbishop of San Salvador,
said the proposal was based on observations about the political,
social, military and economic situation from more than 60
Salvadoran organizations.
   Rebel leader Joaquin Villalobos said the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front, the umbrella organization for five
Salvadoran guerrilla groups, considered the report positive because
it demands ``an end to the war and the reasons that led to it.''
   He and rebel representative Leonel Gonzalez added, however, that
reopening talks with the government would be difficult.
   Rivera Damas presented the report on what he called a ``national
debate'' during a ceremony at a military installation attended by
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's military commander and de
facto ruler.
   Villalobos and Gonzalez met with Noriega and later said they
briefed him on visits by rebel representatives to Peru, Argentina,
Ecuador and Costa Rica to promote a negotiated settlement.
   They said rebel officials would return to those countries to
inform the government leaders of their meeting with the archbishop.
   Rivera Damas said the report contained 140 ideas offered by the
60 organizations in several days of meetings with church leaders,
but he gave no details.
   Salvadoran church leaders have mediated the few meetings between
the government and rebels, and frequently urge that talks resume.
The last meeting was Oct. 20, 1987 in San Salvador, the capital of
El Salvador.
   Gonzalez said the report ``can reactivate the peace process,''
but another round of talks with the government of President Jose
Napoleon Duarte ``isn't easy now.''
   ``Negotiations in El Salvador are quite complicated,'' Gonzalez
said. ``The Americans oppose them, Duarte opposes them, parts of
the private sector oppose them so we have to build relations among
forces to open negotiations.''
   He said the rebels have set no preconditions for talks but
rejected previous government demands that the rebels lay down their
weapons.
   ``We have given them the message that we are ready to talk with
all social forces, including the army, that we are ready to talk at
any place or time,'' Gonzalez said.
   ``The one that's established conditions is the government,'' he
said. ``Duarte has said that in order to talk again with the FMLN
(rebels' front) we have to put down our arms. This is absurd, it's
inadmissible.''
   Venceremos, the clandestine rebel radio, said Monday that
Salvadoran rebels had killed the mayor of a small town in Morazan,
a western province in the war zone. The army said 53 rebels and 29
soldiers were killed in several skirmishes in October.
</TEXT>
