<DOCNO> AP881031-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Kraft 1stLd-Writethru a0767 10-31 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kraft, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0767,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Expected To Make Few Changes After Winning Food
Giant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 15th graf `The combination' to UPDATE
with senator seeking antitrust investigation. Picks up 16th graf
pvs `Maxwell said....' A longer version moved on the business wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The intense, two-week takeover battle for Kraft
Inc. was rather like the storm before the calm, as analysts said
Monday they expect Philip Morris Cos. Inc. to make few changes in
the company it is buying for $13.1 billion.
   ``I suspect we'll have Kraft left alone for a year,'' said
Ronald B. Morrow, who tracks both companies for the investment firm
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Diana Temple, an analyst with Salomon Brothers Inc., agreed,
saying, ``It appears that both companies will be run separately.''
   Morrow based his prediction on Philip Morris' history. ``When
they bought General Foods, they left it alone for two years,'' he
said, referring to the 1985 purchase of another major U.S. food
manufacturer.
   Philip Morris executives did not seek changes in General Foods
until the division began having problems, Morrow noted, adding that
he did not anticipate similar steps to be taken at Kraft.
   ``Kraft manages their business better than General Foods does,''
he said.
   In fact, Philip Morris might draw on Kraft's expertise to help
General Foods' sales and earnings growth, which have flagged in
recent years. ``There are more problems at General Foods that Kraft
could fix,'' Morrow said.
   Kraft and Philip Morris announced Sunday that they had signed an
agreement under which Philip Morris would boost its tender offer
for all of Kraft's outstanding stock to $106 a share from $90. The
Kraft board said it was recommending shareholders accept the deal.
   It appeared Monday Kraft investors would enthusiastically
endorse the acquisition. The company's stock soared $7 a share to
$103.50 on the New York Stock Exchange. Philip Morris rose 62{
cents a share to $95.37{.
   Kraft had bitterly opposed as inadequate the initial $90-a-share
offer Philip Morris made Oct. 17. Kraft then unveiled a defensive
restructuring that would pay stockholders a package of cash and
securities that Kraft valued at $110 a share.
   After negotiations Friday in Chicago, company officials worked
out a preliminary agreement that the Kraft board approved at a
meeting in New York, Philip Morris Chairman Hamish Maxwell said.
   The acquisition _ the largest combination of non-oil companies
in the United States _ would fulfill Philip Morris' goal of
reducing its dependence on revenue from its slowing cigarette
business. It also would become a tougher competitor against other
giant multinational corporations like Unilever, the giant
Anglo-Dutch concern that Philip Morris will displace as the world's
biggest consumer products company.
   ``It will boost Philip Morris' sales from about $30 billion in
1988 to $45.5 billion in 1989,'' Ms. Temple predicted, adding that
the combination ``will boost non-tobacco operations to up to 35
percent of sales.''
   The acquisition would add well-known Kraft labels such as
Velveeta processed cheese, Parkay margarine, Philadelphia cream
cheese, Miracle Whip salad dressing and Sealtest ice cream to
popular Philip Morris brands like Miller beer, Marlboro cigarettes,
Jell-O and Maxwell House coffee.
   The combination also would create the world's second biggest
food products operation after Switzerland's Nestle SA.
   In Washington, D.C., Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum said Monday he
has asked the Federal Trade Commission to launch an antitrust
investigation of the deal. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said the resulting
company would be so large it could seriously affect competition and
raise the prices of prepared foods.
   Metzenbaum is chairman of the Senate Judiciary subcommittee on
antitrust, monopolies and business rights.
   FTC spokesman Howard Shapiro said the agency would not comment
on whether it was looking into the merger.
   Maxwell said there were no plans to sell any major Kraft assets.
   While the analysts expected Kraft and General Foods to exist as
separate entities for the near-future, they said they did not
expect the honeymoon to last forever.
   ``It would make sense if they were combined,'' because the new
company could save on manufacturing, distribution and
administrative costs, Morrow said.
</TEXT>
