<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Opera     10-31 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Opera,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Singer Is Royal Opera Hit In `Butterfly'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American soprano Catherine Malfitano was cheered
after a great performance in the title role of ``Madama Butterfly''
on Monday night at the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden.
   The house had been sold out for weeks for the new production of
Giacomo Puccini's opera by Spanish actress and theater director
Nuria Espert. Ms. Espert shared the acclaim when she joined the
cast and production team in taking 11 curtain calls.
   Few women producers are in the opera business. Ms. Espert, who
has her own theater company in Madrid, has done only one other
opera. But she is quickly adding a reputation for the difficult art
to her fame as an actress and stage director.
   Asked later in a dressing-room interview if she found any
difference between direction by a woman and a man, Ms. Malfitano
replied, ``There isn't any. But Nuria is full of wonderful ideas
and I was able to ask her questions about the role which I would
have been hesitant to put to a man.''
   The New York-born singer added, ``If there is a difference, it's
a sense that she feels things I might feel about the character
because she is a woman. But that's not to say that men aren't
intuitive and sensitive.''
   Ms. Malfitano gave a heart-tugging interpretation of
Cio-Cio-San, the Japanese geisha girl known as Butterfly who falls
in love with U.S. Navy officer Benjamin Franklin Pinkerton.
   In what looks like a very un-Japanese reaction, the singer
writhes on the floor of her tenement apartment when she learns that
Pinkerton has deserted her and intends to take their son away.
   ``Nuria had me do that _ we both have great love for
Cio-Cio-San,'' Ms. Malfitano explained.
   ``We didn't do it from a Japanese viewpoint. This is an opera by
a European and it's a European view of Japan. But I think reaction
to pain and grief is universal.
   ``When we are alone we do things the world would not expect to
see. It's a private moment that's very painful, an extreme moment
we express in an extreme way. It should be shocking and almost
surprising and it has the ring of truth,'' the singer said.
   Ms. Malfitano's dark-eyed beauty was enhanced by her long hair,
worn down to her waist in the role.
   ``Yes, it is my own _ people are always asking me,'' she said,
laughing.
   Her father's parents emigrated to the United States from
Linguaglossa and Fiumefreddo di Sicilia in the foothills of the Mt.
Etna volcano.
   Welsh tenor Arthur Davies, who sang Pinkerton, also said he
found no difference in being directed by a woman.
   Chewing on a piece of butterscotch _ ``It moistens the mouth and
I just happened to have it in my pocket'' _ he said: ``Nuria knows
the piece and it's just a matter of interpretation. It's what she
wanted and I hope we've made sense of it.''
   The opera was first staged as a contemporary story in 1904. Ms.
Espert places it in 1937 to heighten the tension between Americans
and Japanese, four years before the attack at Pearl Harbor. But she
does not transform the story in any way. She said before the first
night she doesn't believe in ``director's opera.''
   ``It is just a fashion. In opera, the true director is the
composer and everything is in the music. You need a very good ear
and to listen carefully,'' Ms. Espert told London's Daily Telegraph.
   The cleverly designed tenement, set on three floors, was by
Italy's Ezio Frigerio. His wife, Franca Squarciapino, did the
costumes.
   Denmark's Michael Schonwandt seemed to draw everything possible
from his conducting of the opera house orchestra.
   Mezzo-soprano Miao Qing, who sang the role of Cio-Cio-San's
servant, Suzuki, in her British debut, is the first Chinese artist
to sing with the Royal Opera and she looked delighted, waving her
bouquet at the audience.
   Ms. Malfitano was given three bouquets and happily carried the
largest of them away with her, walking down Floral Street with her
husband Stephen and friends, looking at the posters of the
production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
