<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Strike     10-31 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Strike,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Workers End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60,000 government workers
ended a five-day strike on Monday after receiving assurances that
Congress would consider their demands .
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo said the return to work may have
prevented a coup.
   ``We passed the test and now it's a question of erasing the
slate and starting over,'' Azcona Hoyo told a news conference.
   ``If there is no understanding and no dialogue, such
abnormalities (as the strike) end in a violent confrontation or a
coup.''
   The workers, members of the National Association of Public
Employees, struck last Wednesday and the armed forces occupied
public buildings until the strike ended Monday morning.
   The strikers demanded paid vacations, improved job security,
civil service reforms and varying pay increases. Their salary now
averages $500 a month.
   No settlement was reached. Azcona Hoyo said he promised no
retaliation would be made against strikers or strike leaders.
   The president said he appointed a Cabinet committee to determine
how the nation of 5 million could pay union demands that the
government estimated could cost $150 million a year. Congress will
take up the issue in December.
   Association leader Carlos Obdulio Chevez said that if the
demands are not met, ``we will go on strike again, because the
suspension of this strike does not mean we are giving up our
demands.''
   Chevez praised Azcona Hoyo, saying the president ``was always
ready to have a dialogue with us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
