<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2303EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ExitPolls 1stLd-Writethru a0809 10-31 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Exit Polls, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0809,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Networks Will Be Allowed To Conduct Exit Polls Under Judge's
Ruling</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 10th graf `The state' with two grafs to UPDATE with
reaction from assistant state attorney general. Adds five grafs
after final graf to add background and reaction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday blocked a state law
that would have banned the three major television networks from
conducting exit polls just outside voting places to predict winners
on election night.
   U.S. District Judge David Doty, saying the law is likely to be
found unconstitutional, issued a preliminary injunction against its
enforcement.
   The 1984 law prohibits voters from being asked how they voted
within 100 feet of the polling place. Nearly half the states have
some limits on exit polling, in part because of fears that voter
turnout will be hampered by early predictions of results.
   The networks targeted Minnesota along with six other states
where they successfully challenged restrictions they considered so
stringent they would effectively ban exit polls.
   Floyd Abrams, a New York lawyer representing CBS, ABC and NBC,
had argued that the Minnesota law violates free speech and would
prevent family members from asking each other how they voted if
they were within the zoned area.
   ``We're delighted,'' Abrams said of Doty's ruling. ``It's a
First Amendment right that the public have that information.
   ``If the voter doesn't want to answer questions he doesn't have
to, but if th voter is willing to answer the questions, he should
be able to be a part of the process.''
   Doty said that one of the principal concerns of the First
Amendment is the free discussion of governmental affairs. He also
said the First Amendment protects the news media's right to gather
information.
   ``Thus, exit polling, which involves gathering and disseminating
information on governmental affairs, is protected by the free
speech clause of the First Amendment,'' Doty wrote.
   Peter Ackerberg, a special assistant state attorney general, had
argued that the Minnesota law was passed to preserve the sanctity
of the polling place, to prevent harassment of voters, to prevent
congestion and confusion around the polling place, and to encourage
voter participation.
   Ackerberg said he would not comment on Doty's ruling until he
sees it Tuesday.
   Doty said legislators who wrote the law were primarily concerned
with ``alleviating the threat that people might be discouraged from
voting if a projection indicates that a particular outcome of an
election is almost a certainty.''
   ``Such a purpose is not a sufficient basis for restricting
otherwise constitutionally protected speech,'' Doty wrote.
   Abrams said the networks have successfully fought similar exit
polling restrictions in Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Montana,
Washington and Wyoming.
   Exit polling became controversial in 1980 when it became clear
after polls closed in the East that Ronald Reagan would defeat
President Jimmy Carter by a landslide. Many Westerners were still
voting when the networks declared Reagan the winner.
   The three networks say this year they will project winners of
the presidential race state-by-state as polls close, but will
refrain from declaring a winner overall until after voters on the
West Coast cast their ballots.
   State Rep. Randy Kelly, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee and a proponent of the law, said the Legislature is not
likely to repeal the exit poll law unless courts declare it
unconstitutional.
   Kelly said exit polls ``might greatly reduce the voting of
people in a democracy.''
   Abrams said the networks may try to obtain a permanent
injunction against the Minnesota law after the election. But he
said the next legal step by the networks will hinge on whether
Minnesota officials ``persist in opposing our efforts'' to conduct
exit polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
