<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Cooray 1stLd-Writethru a0685 10-31 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Cooray, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Announces Death of Sri Lankan Cardinal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name to Cooray throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Thomas B. Cooray, the Roman
Catholic archbishop of Colombo, Sri Lanka, for 29 years until his
retirement in 1976, has died, the Vatican announced Monday. He was
86.
   Cooray died Saturday night in Tewatte Ragama, the Vatican said.
It did not give a cause of death.
   He was archbishop of Colombo from July 26, 1947, until his
retirement on Sept. 2, 1976. Cooray was installed as a cardinal by
Pope Paul VI on Feb. 22, 1965.
   His death leaves 156 members of the College of Cardinals.
   While archbishop, ``Cooray favored a respectful dialogue with
the Buddhists and with other Christians,'' the Vatican said.
``During the years of suppression or limitation of religious
freedom, Cooray constantly affirmed the spirituality of his own
mission and the loyalty of the Roman Catholics (to the
government).''
   Services will be held Thursday.
</TEXT>
