<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SecretService-Suit     10-31 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Secret Service-Suit,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Settles Suit Against Secret Service For $2,500</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The busy presidential campaign helped
persuade the government Monday to settle a false arrest lawsuit
accusing Secret Service agents of beating a bystander during a 1984
raid on counterfeiters, attorneys said.
   The government, which needs the services during the campaign
season of agents who might have had to testify, agreed to pay
Edward Scala of Jersey City $2,500, but admitted no wrongdoing for
the Sept. 8, 1984, incident. Scala had sued for $1 million in
damages.
   ``They're busy,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey D. Smith said
of the agents who would have had to testify and prepare for a
trial. ``This is big crunch time,'' he said, referring to the
comings and goings of the candidates.
   The Secret Service, a branch of the U.S. Treasury Department,
has the duty of protecting political figures and investigating
counterfeiting.
   Scala charged that when agents burst into his Jersey City
building to raid a counterfeiting ring, they handcuffed him, beat
him and dragged him through the hallway and caused him ``severe and
permanent injuries,'' said his lawsuit, which was filed 18 months
later.
   The agents struck Scala in the head, neck and groin, according
to the complaint.
   They also entered his apartment without a proper search warrant,
it said.
   The Treasury Department in November 1985 denied an
administrative settlement, so he went to federal court for damages
and legal costs.
   Smith said Scala was never struck and was only detained after
running away from the agents. He was handcuffed for 30 seconds and
held for under five minutes until agents were told that Scala was a
resident of the building, the attorney said.
   An agent chased Scala into his apartment on the basis of a broad
search warrant, Smith added.
   During the raid, Scala ``was kind of rubbernecking, you might
say,'' Smith said.
   Smith said the afternoon raid netted $7.5 million in counterfeit
currency, the largest such seizure at the time in New Jersey. The
bogus bills were mostly in denominations of $10 and $20. Five
people were arrested and convicted or pleaded guilty, he said.
   Scala, in his 50s, could not be reached for comment. His home
telphone number is not published. His attorney, John Schwartz,
declined to comment on the settlement. He said his client was
unemployed.
   The suit did not specify the nature of Scala's injuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
