<DOCNO> AP881031-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 0816EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-ArsoninWales Adv10   10-31 1145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arson in Wales, Adv 10,1175</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs Nov. 10 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Clandestine Group Steps Up Attacks on English Property in Wales</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLWYN BAY, Wales (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clandestine group calling itself the
Sons of Glendower has stepped up a 9-year-old arson campaign
against English-owned property in Wales, increasing fears that the
attacks will begin to claim lives.
   The group chooses violence to fight what many Welsh oppose _ the
increased immigration of the English into Wales.
   Celtic Wales has been united with Saxon England for 452 years,
but nationalism remains a strong undercurrent in Wales, and the
English influx is widely blamed for diluting the Welsh language and
culture and inflating house prices beyond reach of the local people.
   Such themes are not confined to Wales. Regional nationalism is a
flourishing, often divisive force in this United Kingdom of
England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, not to mention
subdivisions like Cornwall and the Isle of Man, where outsiders'
vacation homes are also a target of local nationalists.
   But in this western, coastal region of Britain, the Welsh
extremists have struck more frequently in recent months and have
pushed across the border to burn down property in England.
   The arsonists, who have their supporters but are shunned by the
nationalist mainstream, also have expanded their targets from
mostly vacation homes to commercial property like real estate
offices, and they have begun using more sophisticated incendiary
time-bombs.
   Nobody expects the attacks to escalate into a conflict like
Northern Ireland's, which has killed about 2,700 people in the past
20 years. But the time-bombs, which could go off at the wrong time
or in the wrong hands, are causing serious concern.
   ``We have been so concerned about this change in tactics,'' said
Inspector John Hughes-Jones at the Colwyn Bay headquarters of the
North Wales police. ``It is a miracle that nobody has been
seriously injured or killed. With the recent escalation, the odds
of that happening are shortening all the time.''
   Recent weeks have seen at least 11 attacks on real estate
offices, shops and a vacation home. Eight of those came on one
weekend in early October over a widespread area of western England.
   Fears also are growing that the campaign might encourage old
prejudices and discourage job-creating inward investment _ problems
Northern Ireland knows well.
   ``Obviously, anything of that sort would not exactly advertise
the place,'' said Roger Mansfield, director of the University of
Wales' Cardiff Business School. ``It has the potential of
developing into a major problem.''
   Since 1979, 19 men have been convicted of arson and damage
offenses, police say, but the force has made no arrests in three
years, and it is being criticized for failing to unmask the Sons of
Glendower.
   Plaid Cymru, the Welsh nationalist party which has three seats
in the 650-member House of Commons, strongly opposes the violent
campaign. Its president, Dafydd Elis Thomas, has called the police
``most ineffective'' and urged the government to apply pressure for
better results.
   The police say they lack evidence partly because the public is
uncooperative.
   ``It's quite a big percentage who (a) obviously know something
but don't want to tell us, or (b) those who know something that
they don't know would help us,'' Hughes-Jones said.
   Wales, brought under English rule by King Edward I in 1282 and
united with England in 1536, has a long history of protest against
its conquerors. In the 1960s, for example, a group called the Free
Welsh Army waged a violent anti-English campaign.
   The Welsh Language Society for years has waged non-violent
protest against English immigration, staging sit-ins in real estate
offices and glueing their locks.
   Non-violent nationalists support measures such as limiting
property sales to English newcomers and imposing higher taxes on
second homes.
   The Sons of Glendower, or Meibion Glyndwyr, take their name from
Owen Glendower, a 15th-century Welsh rebel leader.
   The group is believed to be responsible for most of the 150
arson incidents, counted primarily in rural, picturesque north
Wales since the first attack, on a cottage in Mynydd Nefyn Dec. 13,
1979, police said.
   The group, which initially broke into empty homes and built
simple fires, has made erratic phone calls and delivered letters
claiming responsibity over the years.
   ``The target now (sic) the colonists and the capitalists,'' said
a letter delivered to HTV, the Welsh television station, after
recent attacks on a tackle shop and canoe gear store in Wales.
``They are the enemies of the people. Their free markets are
killing Wales. We demand justice.''
   It was signed Rhys Gethin, who was a lieutenant of Owen
Glendower, police said.
   The extremists' most prominent public supporter is the Welsh
poet R.S. Thomas, a retired minister, who earlier this year
described them as the only true defenders of Welsh language and
culture.
   Owain Williams, a founding member of a new nationalist movement
called Y Cyfamodwyr, or the Covenanters, doesn't go that far, but
says he won't condemn Thomas' stance because ``the situation is
desperate. It needs desperate measures.''
   Williams added: ``They are expected to lie down and take it as a
streamroller crushes them west into the sea. We are becoming the
dispossessed in our own land. This is our last foothold.''
   The British government's Welsh Office says it has no statistics
showing how many of Wales' 2.8 million people are English, but
nationalists say their numbers are multiplying significantly.
   The English are believed to comprise less than 20 percent of
Wales' population but reliable statistics on their numbers and the
migration trend are hard to come by because the British are not
required to register their English or other nationality.
   But Welsh nationalists say the English immigrants' numbers are
multiplying significantly.
   Middle-class English people are taking advantage of a property
boom in southeast England to sell high at home and buy cheaper
homes in Wales, which many believe to be an idyllic spot for
raising a family, as well as for retirement, weekends and vacations.
   A recent revival of the Welsh economy has made it easier for the
English to find jobs in Wales, and many of those who don't find
local employment choose to commute. Some go as far as London, which
is about 200 miles to the southeast, or a train ride of about four
hours from this coastal resort.
   Meanwhile, the percentage of people speaking Welsh, which is
taught in schools and is highly visible on the nation's bilingual
signs, has declined to 64 percent in the Welsh-speaking areas this
year from 71.3 percent in 1981, a recent survey for HTV indicated.
   The survey also showed that 57 percent of the 1,000 people
questioned in west and north Wales supported the aims of the Sons
of Glendower, although only 6 percent endorsed the arson campaign.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Nov. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
