<NOTE>For Release Saturday, Nov. 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, Nov. 12, the 317th day of 1988. There are 49
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On Nov. 12, 1920, baseball got its first ``czar'' as Judge
Kennesaw Mountain Landis was elected commissioner of the American
and National Leagues.
   On this date:
   In 1815, American suffragist Elizabeth Cady Stanton was born in
Johnstown, N.Y.
   In 1921, representatives of nine nations gathered in the
nation's capital for the start of the Washington Conference for
Limitation of Armaments.
   In 1927, Josef Stalin became the undisputed ruler of the Soviet
Union as Leon Trotsky was expelled from the Communist Party.
   In 1929, Grace Kelly _ the future Hollywood star and Princess of
Monaco _ was born in Philadelphia.
   In 1944, during World War II, the German battleship ``Tirpitz''
was sunk off Norway.
   In 1948, former Japanese premier Hideki Tojo and several other
World War II Japanese leaders were sentenced to death by a war
crimes tribunal.
   In 1954, Ellis Island, the immigration station in New York
Harbor, closed after processing more than 20 million immigrants
since its opening in 1892.
   In 1975, Supreme Court Justice William O. Douglas retired
because of failing health, ending a record 36{-year term.
   In 1977, the city of New Orleans elected its first black mayor,
Ernest ``Dutch'' Morial.
   In 1980, the U.S. space probe Voyager 1 came within 77,000 miles
of Saturn, sailing beneath the planet's rings while transmitting
data back to Earth.
   In 1981, budget director David A. Stockman apologized to
President Reagan for comments he'd made to The Atlantic Monthly
expressing doubts about the administration's economic policies.
   In 1982, Yuri V. Andropov was elected to succeed the late Leonid
I. Brezhnev as general secretary of the Communist Party's Central
Committee.
   In 1984, space shuttle astronauts Dale Gardner and Joe Allen
snared a wandering satellite in history's first space salvage. The
Palapa B-2 satellite was secured in Discovery's cargo bay for
return to Earth.
   Ten years ago: Striking Iranian oil workers defied a government
deadline for ending a 13-day-old walkout. Meanwhile, exiled Iranian
religious leader Ayatollah Khomeini, interviewed in Paris, accused
President Jimmy Carter of ``complicating'' the Iranian crisis by
supporting Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi.
   Five years ago: President Reagan, having concluded a visit to
Japan, arrived in South Korea, where he addressed the nation's
parliament, telling its members, ``America is your friend and we
are with you.''
   One year ago: Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega, in Washington
for a meeting of the Organization of American States, announced he
had come up with a ``concrete proposal'' for achieving a cease-fire
with the Contra rebels.
   Birthdays: Supreme Court Justice Harry Blackmun is 80. Actress
Kim Hunter is 66. Musician-songwriter Neil Young is 43. Romanian
gymnast Nadia Comaneci is 27.
   Thought for Today: ``If you try to please everybody, somebody is
not going to like it.'' _ Donald Rumsfeld, former U.S. Secretary of
Defense.
</TEXT>
