<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--DoubtingDisease-I ADV13-1stAdd   10-31 1020</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Doubting Disease-I, ADV 13-1st Add,1042</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: she says.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Obsessions and compulsions can turn up in families previously
untouched by mental illness, but are more likely to cluster in
families with histories of OCD or its frequent companion,
depression.
   Although it affects men and women in equal numbers, children
with OCD are twice as apt to be boys. It often strikes young
adults, but many can recall bouts of obsessive behavior from
childhood, and doctors have spotted it in children as young as 3.
   Obsessive thoughts or compulsive behaviors lurk beneath the
surface in nearly everyone. Most people regard neatness and
exactitude as desirable traits. And who hasn't raced home to
double-check an appliance, worried excessively about cancer, or
gotten a tune ``stuck'' in his head?
   No one can pinpoint where meticulousness or rigidity leave off
and illness begins. Still, the experts agree that the periodic
preoccupations of everyday life bear little resemblance to the
relentless, involuntary, all-consuming nature of OCD.
   At their worst, according to Rapoport, the habits of OCD
patients ``become gross caricatures and distortions of useful
everyday behavior.''
   ``My patients fight exhausting battles with invisible germs
daily, even hourly,'' Rapoport writes in ``The Boy Who Couldn't
Stop Washing,'' the first ``popular'' book on OCD, to be published
by E.P. Dutton in January. Rapoport, who's been treating the
illness since 1972, is hoping the book will lure more victims out
of hiding.
   At the core of the doubting disease is ``the inability to be
reassured by the senses,'' Rapoport writes. Somehow the message _
that the house is clean or the doors are locked _ doesn't get
through. ``In one way or another,'' she says, ``every patient with
OCD wants to know how to know.''
   Unlike gambling, overeating or other activities commonly labeled
``compulsive,'' OCD's senseless rituals bring no pleasure. ``I
hated to count,'' says Mike, a young shoe salesman. ``All I ever
wanted was to stop.''
   Like others with the illness, he had no choice but to keep
counting: steps, stairs, shoes, everything.
   Peggy, a secretary in her 30s with flowing brown hair and a
bubbly, outgoing manner, couldn't stop cleaning, a compulsion that
literally popped up overnight.
   ``One weekend when I was 21, I went away with my family,'' she
recalls. ``We walked into a motel room, and everything felt dirty.
When I brought my clothes home the next day, they felt dirty, too.
That was the beginning.''
   Soon, other things bothered Peggy: ``The drugstore. The
hospital. The garbage truck. Anything that had to do with germs or
disease.''
   On a good day, Peggy bathed with bar soap and water. On bad
days, she scrubbed her skin raw with Lysol. ``I stashed Lysol all
over the house, like an alcoholic hides booze. I carried it in my
purse.''
   Over time, Peggy's life became more and more disrupted. Though
lonely, she stayed away from her parents and turned down dates to
protect others from her ``contamination.''
   She did much of her work twice: once at the office and again at
home, where she put on rubber gloves and copied everything over on
``clean'' paper. She bypassed the corner grocery and drove to
distant supermarkets, so as not to contaminate any stores she might
one day need to go back to.
   ``If I'd buy a new outfit, suddenly it would be contaminated.
You either washed it to death or threw it out. I looked like hell.
I couldn't use makeup because I'd contaminate it, and how many
times can you afford to throw away your makeup and buy all new
stuff?''
   April, whose symptoms were similar, became her own plumber and
repairman. Her house was off-limits to all but her husband and
sons; as soon as they got home at night, they were required to use
the shower April had installed in the basement. Showering in the
upstairs bathroom was forbidden.
   Though she had two children and a full-time teaching job, April
couldn't accept help with the housework. ``I would have no way of
knowing what my husband had touched before he picked out our
groceries or whatever.''
   Her sons weren't allowed to go to movies or play in the yard but
were confined to a concrete patio April hosed down each morning. At
school, she couldn't use the bathroom no matter how long her day,
and she retreated to her classroom whenever hallways were crowded.
If a student inadvertently bumped her, it would bother her for a
week.
   ``What was life like? It was hell,'' says April, a neatly
dressed middle-aged woman with short, graying hair, a tense mouth
and reddened eyes that burn with sorrow. ``If you have a cancer or
a heart condition, you can be consoled. With this, you'd be
ostracized. You have to hide it. People would think my judgment is
impaired, even though I'm a good teacher.''
   Her eyes fill and her voice quavers as she recalls her medical
history: ``I've been hospitalized, put on medications, given shock
treatments. The psychiatrists said to restrain me. To take away all
my buckets.''
   Unlike April, who for 20 years never stopped seeking help, Peggy
would still be hiding if a friend hadn't found out and urged her to
get treatment. Otherwise, she might never have known her terrible
secret had a name.
   Many doctors don't know either, often mistaking OCD for
depression or schizophrenia. ``Physicians want to diagnose things
they can treat,'' says Rapoport, who adds that until recently, her
profession had little to offer OCD patients.
   For the time being, most doctors view OCD as a chronic illness
that can be controlled but not cured. But given stepped-up research
by scientists and drug companies around the world, the prognosis is
increasingly hopeful.
   Meanwhile, April waits. After seven years of drug and behavior
treatments, she feels more in control of the illness that has
tormented her for 21 years. But she knows she has yet to break free.
   ``My son wants to come home from college for Thanksgiving and
shower upstairs,'' she says sadly. ``I don't think I'm ready for
that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
