<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1414EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--Hmong-Opium ADV13   10-31 0936</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Hmong-Opium, ADV 13,0964</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ In the large colonies of Hmong refugees in St.
Paul, Minn., and Fresno, Calif., police are noticing a dramatic
increase in the use of opium, a powerful narcotic that was part of
the culture in Southeast Asia. Federal customs agents have seized
450 shipments of opium bound for Minnesota in the past five years
and they figure that's only a fraction of the amount that got
through.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the cold-cream containers mailed to
Xiong Yer Khang from Laos, U.S. Customs inspectors discovered globs
of a black, tar-like substance.
   It was opium, police say, a powerful narcotic from which heroin
and morphine are derived. It's also part of a culture many Hmong
refugees weren't willing to leave behind in Southeast Asia.
   Federal and local authorities say opium smoking is on the rise
in Hmong communities across the country.
   ``It's very cheap, very available, and we're seeing more young
people addicted,'' says Dr. Joseph Westermeyer, who oversees the
treatment of Hmong opium addicts at the University of Minnesota
Hospital in Minneapolis.
   ``It looks like the coming thing,'' says police Lt. Joe Carvalho
of Fresno, Calif., where police recently pulled more than 5,000 red
and violet opium poppies from a Hmong family's backyard garden.
   ``We expect a lot of the Hmong community are using opium because
it's an accepted practice in their own country. We're just trying
to be more aware of what's happening in the Hmong community,
communicate to them that it is not accepted.''
   The Hmong, who fought on the American side during the Vietnam
War, fled to the United States from their native Laos by the tens
of thousands after the end of the war.
   No one knows how many Hmong refugees are smoking opium, but
experts say the stress of adjusting to a radically different
environment accelerates the slide toward addiction.
   ``The stress, frustrations, prejudices, language problem and
family problems probably contribute'' to heavy opium use, says
David Yang, a Hmong community services officer with the St. Paul
Police Department.
   The drug hinders the process of learning to succeed in a new
culture. ``In the United States, I have never seen an opium user
who has a full-time job,'' Yang says.
   ``They are taking food literally out of their families'
mouths,'' adds Westermeyer, an expert on Hmong culture who spent a
decade working in Laos. ``They're not learning the language, not
learning to survive.''
   Fresno, with about 20,000 Hmong, and St. Paul, with about
12,000, have the largest U.S. populations of the refugees from the
mountains and jungles of Laos. Smaller Hmong communities are
scattered around the country in Wisconsin, Missoula, Mont.,
Providence, R.I., and elsewhere.
   St. Paul police gained a new appreciation of the opium problem
last winter when federal customs agents showed them a computer
printout of 450 Minnesota-bound shipments seized in the last five
years, says police Lt. Richard Dugan, head of the narcotics unit.
The seized shipments _ believed to be only a small fraction of the
number that made it through _ ranged in size from a few ounces to
more than 10 pounds.
   Khang, 39, whom police believe is a major opium supplier to St.
Paul's Hmong, is awaiting trial on a charge of narcotics possession
with intent to distribute, as well as a federal narcotics
importation charge. Authorities arrested him in March after
intercepting the cold-cream shipment and then keeping his home
under surveillance.
   Minnesota authorities worry that seizures haven't kept pace with
the flow of the drug into the area.
   There is just one other opium case pending in St. Paul now,
Dugan says. There have been only about 10 opium arrests in the Twin
Cities area in the last decade, says Dick Hendrie, U.S. Customs
narcotics group supervisor in Minneapolis.
   In California's Sacramento Valley, seizures of opium ``have
increased substantially over the last couple years,'' says Orve
Hendrix, resident agent in charge of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration's Fresno office.
   ``What were once a few ounces now are 10 pounds or so at a
time,'' he says.
   Police have sometimes been overly tolerant of opium use by the
Hmong.
   ``There was a feeling, `How can you prosecute this poor old man
who fled his country and brought his custom with him?''' Dugan
says. ``And how do you prosecute someone who doesn't realize he
broke the law?''
   In his 1983 book, ``Poppies, Pipes and People: Opium and Its Use
in Laos,'' Westermeyer notes that opium is commonly used as
medicine by a native population short on doctors and pharmacies.
And by custom, he says, respectable households keep some on hand
for guests and special occasions.
   But Westermeyer maintains that heavy use of the poppy's fruit is
no more accepted in Laos than it is here.
   In contrast to St. Paul and Fresno, police in Green Bay, Wis.,
and Missoula, Mont., report no opium problems in their sizable
Hmong communities.
   ``The Hmong people in Montana have acclimated very well,'' says
Missoula police Capt. Bill Foust. ``To my knowledge, there is no
opium use. Either that or we're not on the ball.''
   Dugan says, ``We know there's a lot of it coming in, but we
don't see the problem on the street.
   ``There's always the possibility it will seep out of the Hmong
community into the general population. Then we do have a problem.''
   End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 13
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1415EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--SingingProsecutor ADV13   10-31 0964</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Singing Prosecutor, ADV 13,1004</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ He's a Pennsylvania prosecutor with a penchant
for performing, getting his message across to the jury with a few
lines from a song. Paul Petro doesn't claim to be another
Pavarotti, or even a Prince, but to him singing is more effective
than boring speeches.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They call him the singing prosecutor, a
legal eagle given to serenading the judge and jury.
   His trials, one critic says, ``have taken a turn for the verse.''
   A judge complains that singing in court makes light of serious
business.
   No matter, says Assistant District Attorney Paul Petro, singing
often beats a lot of talking.
   ``I don't fancy myself a singer, but I think it's an effective
means of communication,'' Petro says.
   In recent months, the 55-year-old prosecutor has entertained
courtrooms in southwestern Pennsylvania's Washington County with
excerpts from ``Home Sweet Home,'' ``Moonlight and Roses'' and
``Pennies from Heaven.''
   ``A trial attorney can be very effective if he uses references
to literature or poetry that are known by everybody,'' Petro says.
   ``Frankly, I don't think there's anything different in reciting,
say, a famous quotation or excellent poem than singing a couple
lines of a song. After all, when you think about it, the best
writers of concise English are really the lyricists.''
   His latest, tuneful tour de force came during the September
trial of a woman charged with stealing two country music cassettes
from a department store.
   ``Every time it rains, it rains pennies from heaven,'' Petro
crooned during his opening argument. ``Don't you know each cloud
contains, pennies from heaven. You'll find your fortune falling all
over town.''
   He suddenly switched from song to speech, without missing a beat.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen of the jury, the defendant's fortune was
falling all over Gee Bee Department Store,'' he recalls telling the
jury. Then, he says, ``I went into the facts.''
   ``Singing helps to focus the jury's attention to certain things
and to listen to the arguments,'' Petro says. ``But in the great
majority of cases, the jury will follow the facts.''
   Robert McGrew, jury foreman for the retail theft trial, said the
guilty verdict, indeed, was based on testimony and evidence.
   ``Singing just didn't seem appropriate, but that's my opinion.
We didn't discuss it,'' says McGrew, 49, who manages a welding and
fabricating business.
   Juror Tony Gregor, 71, a retired feed mill worker, laughed out
loud and slapped his knee when Petro broke into ``Pennies from
Heaven.''
   ``I was surprised. You very seldom hear anybody singing that
song,'' Gregor says, chuckling. ``Everybody was laughing. Something
new, you know?''
   Washington County Common Pleas Judge David Gilmore was not
amused. It was the second time Petro had burst into song in his
courtroom.
   ``I don't think anything he's done has been prejudicial or I
would have stopped it,'' Gilmore says. ``My only objection is that
it makes light of what is a very serious matter.''
   The Observer-Reporter newspaper noted on the editorial page
following the retail theft trial that Petro ``has done nothing
really wrong here, other than to trivialize the judicial system.''
   ``Save us from the singing prosecutor,'' the headline pleaded.
His trials take ``a turn for the verse,'' Managing Editor Park
Burroughs wrote.
   Criticism, much of it tongue-in-cheek, also has come from
defense attorneys. One lawyer suggested that Petro consider
``Jailhouse Rock.''
   ``Of course, that's not my speed nor would I,'' Petro said.
``That would be inappropriate.''
   Petro insists his musical selections always are relevant,
thankfully few and far between, and in good taste.
   He chose ``Home Sweet Home'' for his opening argument in a
February murder trial before Gilmore, his courtroom singing debut,
to ``indicate this great tragedy occurred in a guy's home.''
   ``It just seemed right to sing,'' says Petro, a baritone. ``I
didn't bother to ask anybody. Probably it's a good thing I didn't.
They would have said, `You're nuts.'''
   In May, Petro put on another a cappella performance, this time
the first line of ``Moonlight and Roses,'' to show that an alleged
burglary occurred on a moonlit night.
   ``Pennies from Heaven'' was Petro's most spontaneous rendition.
He decided to give the defendant ``some special treatment'' for
fear she might be acquitted because of the relative insignificance
of the alleged crime.
   In all three instances, ``it's something I've felt is
appropriate,'' he says. ``I feel it's proper. It's not demeaning.
We're not reducing the courtroom to a variety show.''
   Petro is modest about his signing talents.
   ``I've sung in the church choir, but I've never pretended to be
a soloist,'' he says.
   Every time he's sung, he's won. As a result, Washington County
District Attorney John C. Pettit doesn't object.
   ``Paul does a good job,'' Pettit says. ``I entrust to him some
of the more difficult and complicated cases that come into the
office. If from time to time he feels a certain thing is going to
aid him in making the jury understand his point, then I certainly
don't see anything wrong with it.''
   For Petro, verse is superior to verbosity.
   ``I don't know if you've ever bothered to read court opinions,''
he says. ``They're not considered great literature. I mean, they're
well-written. But they're not the type of material that really
stimulates people.''
   Singing, on the other hand, ``is very effective. I think the
people like it. No question about it because, unfortunately, too
many speeches in the courtroom are boring.''
   Petro has no idea when or what he'll sing next.
   ``To use a pun,'' he says, ``you've got to play it by ear.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
