<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GliderPilot ADV13   10-31 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Glider Pilot, ADV 13,0853</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Unlike other proud fighting units in World War
II, such as the paratroopers and PT boat crews, the glider pilots
have been all but forgotten. The National World War II Glider
Pilots Association, which has about 1,300 members and was
instrumental in establishing a Silent Wings Museum in Terrell,
Texas, is dedicated to correcting that oversight.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were called the silent wings. The men
who flew them had a ``G'' _ for guts _ emblazoned on the silver
wings they wore on their uniforms.
   ``The mass of Americans don't know a thing about the gliders,''
says Bard Coatsworth of Lincoln, a former state commander of the
National World War II Glider Pilots Association.
   ``I decided it's time that we stop sitting around telling old
war stories and let the world know about the contribution of
gliders to the war effort.''
   Gliders owe their military history to the Germans, who were
banned as part of the Versailles Treaty from manufacturing aircraft
with engines, Coatsworth said.
   ``They used them to fly demolition experts across the lines into
France at night to destroy the pillboxes and guardposts.''
   Coatsworth was working at the Lincoln Aviation Institute _ the
same place Charles Lindbergh learned to fly _ when he heard the
Army was looking for experienced pilots for glider training.
   He signed up in July 1942 and wound up at Ong Flying School in
Goodland, Kan., where he got 25 hours of training, landing without
power from various altitudes, day and night.
   From there, it was on to two air bases in Texas and more night
and day dead-stick flying, with some practice in gliders made from
converted power aircraft.
   He got his first glimpse of the Waco CG4A (C for combat, G for
glider) in Lubbock, Texas, and remembers wondering, ``How could
anybody fly a thing like this.''
   The gilder, with a wingspan of 83 feet, 8 inches, an overall
length of 48 feet, 3} inches, and a height of 12 feet and 7-odd
inches, ``looked like a big olive green bomber,'' he says.
   It wasn't designed to be pretty.
   ``It was an aerial truck,'' Coatsworth says, ``but the power
pilots who criticized it didn't know what they were missing. It
handled like a dream.''
   Although the war ended before Coatsworth had to fly a glider in
combat, he did have some rather harrowing experiences during
training.
   Once the tow rope broke loose from the power aircraft pulling
the glider and narrowly missed breaking the windshield of the
glider. The rope became tangled around the landing gear and
Coatsworth had to maneuver the craft through a clearing in some
trees to land.
   Snagging the rope would have resulted in a crash, he said.
   On a night run, Coatsworth and his co-pilot had to cut free
because they were incorrectly signaled that the tow plane was in
trouble. Coatsworth and his co-pilot had a choice of landing on a
highway with traffic or at a rock quarry.
   ``We set it down about 20 feet short of the edge of the quarry,
in snake-infested country,'' he says. ``We spent the night on the
wing until they found us in the morning.''
   Coatsworth, assigned to the 66th Squadron of the 403rd Troop
Carrier Group, said the CG4A could carry 13 soldiers and a crew of
two. Some carried mini-bulldozers, Jeeps or mortars.
   The gliders were first used in the war on July 9, 1943, when
they carried British airborne troops from an airfield in Tunisia to
Axis-held Sicily.
   In February 1944, gliders carried troops and equipment behind
enemy lines in Burma to set up landing areas to be used in a
massive air assault that surprised the Japanese.
   Gliders played a key role in the D-day invasion of Normandy on
June 6, 1944, and saw action in southern France, Holland, Bastogne
and Varsity.
   ``They were slated to join forces for a final airborne assault
on Japan proper, but we dropped the big one before it came to
that,'' Coatsworth says.
   Coatsworth says the National World War II Glider Pilots
Association, formed in 1971, has about 1,300 members. He estimates
there were probably 10,000 men trained to fly gliders.
   The association was instrumental in establishing a Silent Wings
Museum in Terrell, Texas, near Dallas, where people can view one of
several restored CG4A gliders and other memorabilia.
   ``My big concern now is that we get our proper place in
history,'' Coatsworth says.
   ``All the other services _ the paratroopers, the PT boat crews,
and the like _ have gotten theirs, and I don't deny them that. But
it's time now for the country to recognize the glider pilots.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1419EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek ADV13   10-31 0872</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, ADV 13,0898</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   LOS ANGELES _ ABC's ``War and Remembrance,'' the sequel to ``The
Winds of War,'' is more of a megaseries than a miniseries.
   Filmed at a cost of $104 million, it will run at least 30 hours,
making it the most expensive and the longest-running film project
of all time.
   The first 18 hours will be televised on seven nights over an
11-day period beginning Sunday. The final 12 hours are still being
edited for showing after the first of the year. However, the exact
number of hours will not be determined until the editing is
completed.
   ``The Winds of War'' and ``War and Remembrance'' are based on
the best-selling novels by Herman Wouk. The first told of the
coming of World War II. The second is about the winning of the war.
   The first miniseries ran 18 hours in February 1983 and attracted
an estimated 140 million viewers.
   The sequel, which includes 1,785 scenes, was filmed at 267
locations in six countries over a 14-month period. It has 358
speaking parts.
   Robert Mitchum continues his role as Victor ``Pug'' Henry, the
naval officer who was on the scene for many of the events leading
up to the war in ``The Winds of War.'' In the new show he is
promoted to admiral and participates in the major sea battles in
the Pacific.
   But the sequel also will feature some new faces in starring
roles.
   Hart Bochner, rejected as too young for ``The Winds of War,''
grew into the role for the sequel.
   Nearly eight years ago, Bochner met with producer-director Dan
Curtis to talk about the role of Byron Henry, the youngest son of
Pug Henry, who marries Natalie Jastrow (Ali MacGraw) in Italy just
as World War II begins.
   ``Dan felt I was too young,'' Bochner says.
   Instead, the role in the 1983 miniseries went to Jan-Michael
Vincent.
   Bochner picks up the role of Byron Henry a few days after Pearl
Harbor. He is a submarine officer in action in the Pacific.
Natalie, who is Jewish, is trapped in Europe and is trying to stay
one step ahead of the Nazis. Natalie, now played by Jane Seymour,
is accompanied by their child, Louis, and her Uncle Aaron.
   Sir John Gielgud takes over the role of Aaron Jastrow from John
Houseman.
   Victoria Tennant, Polly Bergen, David Dukes, Peter Graves, Chaim
Topol, Jeremy Kemp and Ralph Bellamy return in their roles from the
first miniseries.
   The story, Bochner says, ``focuses on the family and how their
lives are affected by the war.''
   ``You don't get just an overview,'' he says. ``You get details
because somebody from the family is usually there. You see me in
the submarine, my dad on the battleships, Natalie at Auschwitz, my
sister's husband at Los Alamos developing the bomb.''
   Since completing the miniseries, Bochner has also starred with
Bruce Willis in ``Die Hard'' and went to Argentina for a
psychological thriller called ``Apartment Zero.''
   Bochner, the son of actor Lloyd Bochner, made his film debut
during his college freshman year as one of the sons of George C.
Scott in ``Islands in the Stream.'' He didn't work again until he
graduated, then played the bad guy in ``Breaking Away.'' He has
worked mostly in feature films and miniseries.
   This is the third miniseries Bochner has been opposite Jane
Seymour. In the first, ``East of Eden,'' he was her son. In the
second, ``The Sun Also Rises,'' he was her love interest. And in
``War and Remembrance,'' they are married.
   ``I was working on `Making Mr. Right' when I signed for the
role,'' he says. ``I read the books to get acquainted with the
character. I'd never seen `Winds of War' because I was out of the
country when it came out. So I stayed away from it. I wanted to
have my own interpretation.
   ``Byron in the beginning is not terribly focused. For lack of a
better reason, he gets involved in the Navy because of parental
pressure. He had been studying art in Europe. It was his boyishness
and brashness and passion that appealed to this older woman.''
   Bochner spent several months in Europe for the sequences in
which he becomes a naval courier and attempts to find his wife and
child. But most of his scenes are at sea aboard submarines.
   The Navy has only two World War II diesel submarines, so it was
necessary to tow a boat on display at Pearl Harbor out to sea.
   To prepare for the role, Bochner spent a week aboard a nuclear
submarine operating off California.
   ``When we shot the battle sequences I thought at first something
had gone wrong with the special effects,'' says Bochner. ``The
explosions were so powerful. They rocked the whole boat.
   ``We filmed under some pretty tough conditions. The temperature
inside the sub never got below 110 degrees. We worked 15 hours a
day. Our objective was to re-create life exactly as it was on a
submarine _ hot, exhausting and frightening.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
