<1ST_LINE>s i BC-AMoscowMeal ADV13   10-31 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-A Moscow Meal, ADV 13,0410</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Planning Simple Meal is All-Day Affair for Moscow Housewife</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Feeding the Soviets, b0518</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before clocking in at her job in central Moscow
one recent morning, Nina Ivanova was already working to find the
makings of that night's dinner for herself and her husband.
   By the time she finished, she had spent two hours 17 minutes in
lines, taken a side trip on a streetcar, and paid a total of 14
rubles ($22.80). Although Ms. Ivanova earns more than the average
industrial worker's salary of 200 rubles ($322) a month, the meal
turned out to be an expensive one not only in money but also in
time.
   In the morning, Ms. Ivanova stood in line for 20 minutes at a
Moscow supermarket to buy two frozen chickens. The scrawny looking
fowl, sold in plastic bags, cost 4.72 rubles ($7.69), or $1.30 a
pound, heads and feet included.
   Mrs. Ivanova was late to work because of the delay. She worked
until 6 p.m., and then took the subway to Lenin Prospekt in the
city's southwest.
   At a butcher's shop, Mrs. Ivanova waited in line for 43 minutes
to buy beef for the beet soup, or borscht, she had decided to
prepare. The meat, enough for generous helpings for two people,
cost her 3.75 rubles ($6.11).
   She then hopped on a streetcar and rode for 15 minutes to a
vegetable store. Once more she stood in line, this time for 37
minutes, and bought beets, cabbage, potatoes and some grapes for
dessert. Cost: 3.43 rubles ($5.59).
   One ingredient was still missing for the borscht _ sour cream.
Lugging her purchases, Mrs. Ivanova walked to a milk shop, where
she waited 22 minutes to buy an enormous dollop of the cream the
Russians call ``smetana.'' It cost 1.70 rubles ($2.77).
   There was one final stop for Mrs. Ivanova _ the bakery. She
stood in line there for 15 minutes to buy two loaves of bread for
40 kopecks (65 cents).
   When Mrs. Ivanova returned home to her one-room apartment, it
was 8:30 p.m. By the time she and her husband sat down to a dinner
of borscht, fried chicken, mashed potatoes and grapes, it was 11:30
p.m.
   According to Mrs. Ivanova, it was an all-too-typical day.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0262 </DOCNO>
