<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1346EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   10-31 1175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,1219</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A glistening, half-naked muscleman strikes a
huge gong to signal the beginning of some of cinema's most
cherished products _ the movies from the Rank Organization.
   From the 1940s through '60s, Rank films dominated British
filmmaking with such gems as ``Great Expectations,'' ``Blythe
Spirit'' and ``Brief Encounter.'' The company made stars out of
Dirk Bogarde, James Mason and Jean Simmons.
   Rank stopped making feature movies in 1980. But its treasure
trove of delightful comedies, melodramas and historical epics is
available for the home screen from Paramount Home Video, including
``Doctor in the House'' (1954), ``The Captain's Table'' (1958) and
``Carry on Doctor'' (1968), which is part of the outrageous ``Carry
On'' series. The videos all retail for $19.95 and are unrated.
   ``Doctor in the House,'' starring Bogarde, Kenneth More, Kay
Kendall and James Robertson Justice, tracks the misadventures of
four overage medical school students at St. Swithin's Hospital. One
is determined to flunk out so he can continue collecting an
allowance from his wealthy aunt; another wants only to play rugby;
a third is a womanizer; the fourth just might make a good doctor.
The movie inspired a TV series and several sequels.
   Elsewhere in video news, Vestron Video will release a new
National Geographic series in December: ``The Superliners: Twilight
of an Era,'' in which life aboard the Queen Elizabeth 2 is
explored; ``Rocky Mountain Beaver Pond,'' a day in the life of the
frisky and busy little rodent; ``The Secret Leopard,'' the elusive
cat and its habits on the Masai Mara Game Reserve in Kenya.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Gaby _ A True Story,'' ``Frantic,''
``The Unholy.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Gaby _ A True Story'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video;
VHS-Beta, $79.95; Rated R).
   
   ``Gaby _ A True Story'' is a remarkable film based on a
remarkable life.
   Gaby Brimmer was born severely disabled by cerebral palsy, very
intelligent but able to communicate only by moving her left foot.
With the help of a devoted nanny and loving parents, she
perseveres, graduates from college and becomes a successful writer.
Her proud spirit, good humor and insight triumph again and again.
   ``Gaby'' is reminiscent of ``The Miracle Worker,'' especially
because the nanny (Norma Aleando in an Oscar-nominated performance)
is so central to Gaby's emergence from her isolation.
   Rachel Levin is wonderful as Gaby, able to convey a range of
emotions with just her left leg and very limited facial
expressions. Robert Loggia and Liv Ullmann also give excellent
performances as Gaby's parents, who refuse to give up on their
daughter and never fail to show their love.
   Her father says, ``Your foot can write the same words as any
philosopher or poet. I refuse to pity you.'' Such support gives her
the strength to fight and win admission to public school.
   Director Luis Mandoki takes chances and succeeds, dealing
frankly and romantically with sex between disabled people. His film
also is forthright about the frustrations Gaby and a disabled
friend feel. It's easy to recognize her anger when Gaby writes,
typing with her big toe: ``God is a fly on the wall. Nanny, give me
a flyswatter.''
   The movie also succeeds at showing what Gaby has in common with
all young people _ she tries makeup and beer; there's a peace sign
on the back of her wheelchair; she falls in love.
   ``Gaby'' is warm and witty, funny and sweet. It's easy to watch
on a television screen, and well worth seeing.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Frantic'' (Warners Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95; Rated R)
   
   ``Frantic'' is a modest Roman Polanski thriller that takes a
plot idea better suited to an hourlong TV drama and pads it into a
two-hour movie.
   Harrison Ford plays an American heart surgeon who arrives with
his wife (Betty Buckley) for a convention in Paris, only to have
her mysteriously abducted from their hotel room while he is in the
shower.
   His desperation and determination to find her lead him into the
Parisian underworld and an unlikely alliance with a young French
girl of dubious morals (Emmanuelle Seigner). She is far-and-away
the most interesting character in the movie and deserves better
than the fate (shades of ``Chinatown'') that she suffers at
Polanski's hands.
   Polanski invites comparisons to the great Alfred Hitchcock with
this story of an ordinary man thrust into peril through no fault of
his own. But the mood of believable, this-could-happen-to-anyone
suspense is shattered after the first half-hour or so and the film
becomes a series of improbable chases and confused confrontations.
   Ford has to carry most of the movie and tries hard, but his
range of expression varies only from extremely anguished to
somewhat anguished.
   All in all, a disappointment from the creator of such original
and unsettling films as ``Knife in the Water,'' ``Repulsion'' and
``Rosemary's Baby.''
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Unholy'' (Vestron Video; VHS-Beta, $89.98; Rated R)
   
   One wonders what Hal Holbrook, Ned Beatty, Trevor Howard and Ben
Cross are doing in a limp horror movie called ``The Unholy.'' The
unemployment lines must be real long in movieland to make such
celebrated and talented actors want to embarrass themselves in the
Camilo Vila film.
   The premise is a good one: A horrific demon exists and can only
be brought down by the purest of mortal souls. However, the
filmmakers cloud the issue with loose ends and vagueness and a
plodding plot.
   The action, such as it is, takes place in New Orleans where two
priests are brutally slain at St. Agnes Church. Enter Father
Michael (Ben Cross). He takes over the parish, resists temptation
from a young woman named Millie who works at a satanic club, is
told by an old blind priest that he is the ``chosen one'' and must
fight a demon.
   So far, so good.
   But then Millie finds a book that talks about a demon called the
Unholy, who preys on the innocent. Millie, an unbelievable virgin,
thinks the demon is after her, naturally. To save her soul, she
thinks she should give herself to Father Michael. Ahem.
   The movie quickly rolls downhill from there culminating in the
bloody and silly clash between Father Michael and the demon.
   It's not a bad diversion for the home screen. But if you're a
fan of the supernatural, you'll want something a little more
devilish.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
