<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov 11-13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Liberated From Chopin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pianist Krystian Zimerman has come a long way
since the days when audiences only wanted to hear him play Chopin.
   At the Nov. 14 Carnegie Hall gala celebrating the 45th
anniversary of Leonard Bernstein's conducting debut with the New
York Philharmonic, he'll be soloist in Bernstein's ``The Age of
Anxiety.'' Next year he'll record all the Beethoven concertos with
Bernstein conducting the Vienna Philharmonic.
   On Dec. 1, Zimerman will perform the North American premiere of
Witold Lutoslawski's ``Piano Concerto'' with the New York
Philharmonic and conductor Zubin Mehta. He played the world
premiere at the Salzburg Festival during the summer with the
composer conducting.
   ``I'm entirely devoted this time to contemporary music,'' the
32-year-old pianist said in an interview. ``I want to show a
different side, because I was usually playing the romantic and
classical repertory.''
   Zimerman has two new recordings out on Deutsche Grammophon, a
Chopin recital, his first Chopin recording in eight years, Liszt's
``Totentanz'' and two concertos, with the Boston Symphony conducted
by Seiji Ozawa.
   DG has a recording of Richard Strauss' ``Sonata in E flat for
Violin and Piano,'' by Zimerman and Kyung Wha Chung, ready to be
released.
   Zimerman was born in Zabrze, Poland. His father, an architect,
started teaching him piano at 5, and soon hired him a teacher.
   ``He was 24; I was 7,'' Zimerman said. ``Today I look back _ I
think it was a blessing I was his first pupil. He didn't have any
fixed idea of how learning should go. I could play the most
difficult pieces because I wanted to play them.
   ``He said OK to the Rachmaninoff `Piano Concerto' when I was 12.
I looked forward so much to play this piece I made progress much
quicker than playing scales.
   ``I had the opportunity to play concerts, which I think is
important for a kid, to know what you're working for. Music doesn't
exist without the person who's listening to it.''
   Zimerman remembers growing up in the communist world. ``There
were not toys for children,'' he said. ``A piano at home was a big
toy. You push a key and the sound is coming, something really
incredible. I spent a lot of time sitting at the piano. We were a
very poor family. I felt somehow rich.''
   He filled in when his father and his musical friends played
chamber music. ``I played all the parts. You look at a score and
you can swallow it immediately. That gives you a very important
skill to play chamber music, which for a pianist is incredibly
important.
   ``A pianist can go through life without playing one note with
anybody else. You can phrase however you like,'' he said. ``Chamber
music puts you back into the right way of controlling yourself. You
can't just fly around with phrases as you like.''
   At 19 he was the youngest of 118 entrants in the 1975 Chopin
Competition in Warsaw. He won.
   ``When you get older, it is more difficult to play in
competitions,'' the pianist said. ``I wasn't aware of many things
and that helped me a lot. My teacher never prepared me to play in a
competition. He said, `You play your music, love the music and
don't care if someone else plays better or not.'
   ``A jurist said to me when I asked him why did he chose me,
`When you started to play, it was like it was fun. We just enjoyed
it.' It is amazing that people can hear anything after 30 pianists.
It is the reason I never want to be on a jury. I would probably
have terrible doubts and gray hair after voting, if it was the
right decision or not.''
   Zimerman's career began after his win, but went slowly for about
four years. He couldn't afford to stay and tour in a town where
he'd played. ``In Paris I wanted to hear other concerts, to be in
this atmosphere. That was extremely difficult. It took awhile until
I was ready to fill the season with so many concerts I could make
my existence and could have time to practice and learn new
repertory.
   ``What helped a lot were recordings and the fact that Bernstein
invited me in 1976 to perform in London,'' he said. ``I think he
got a tape from the competition. In 1979, Claudio Abbado invited me
to his first concert as music director of the London Symphony, to
open the season.
   ``At the beginning, no agent wanted to accept me for anything
but just Chopin,'' Zimerman recalled. ``For almost two years I just
played Chopin recitals. It is beautiful music but it is like having
the same dish all the time.
   ``So I have tried to expand in all possible directions. On my
first recital in America I played some Chopin and some Szymanowski.
He was a great Polish composer nobody plays in the West. He wrote a
lot for piano. It would make about 10 records and every piece is
something.''
   Lutoslawski, who also is from Poland, wrote his concerto for
Zimerman over the last 10 years. ``We were always phoning each
other, meeting and talking about it. It's a beautiful concerto,
solid writing without any tricks.''
   Zimerman is interested in more than music: ``I get 22 monthly
magazines about all the fields of science, psychology and art,'' he
said. ``I try to resist this specializing in a narrow field. If you
look at a tree and know how it grows, you can live more
consciously.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 11-13</NOTE>
