<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Richards ADV11-13   10-31 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Richards, ADV 11-13,0865</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 11-13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: The Future of the Stones in Doubt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Keith Richards and Mick Jagger were like wedded
jewels in the rock world, two diamonds in the rough who made the
Rolling Stones shimmer for almost three decades.
   Now that union has become a little jagged at the edge: A feud
between the guitarist and the lead singer has left the legendary
group's future in doubt.
   Over the past two years, Jagger has pursued a solo career.
Richards has just come out with his first solo LP, ``Talk Is
Cheap,'' and will give his first solo concert Nov. 29 at the Beacon
Theater in New York.
   ``I tell him he's blowing 20-odd years of integrity of the
Stones because he's got a problem,'' the 43-year-old Richards said
in an interview at his Manhattan office, where pictures of the rock
star line the walls.
   ``I ask him, `What's your problem. What's so tough about being
Mick Jagger?' Suddenly you got to complete and be fashionable. The
Stones don't need that. I love the guy and I love to work with him
but I don't understand this star trip he's on.''
   On his new album Richards has a song especially for his longtime
friend, ``You Don't Move Me.'' It begins like the Stones' ``Honky
Tonk Woman,'' with guitar and drums.
   The lyrics say: ``What makes you so greedy? What makes you so
seedy? Why do you think you got no friends? You drove them all
around the bend.''
   ``The melody and the beat came about like they usually do,''
Richards said. ``Songs come to you; you don't make them. They
decide that they're going to visit for a while.''
   Richards said he wrote the song about Jagger on the advice of
drummer Steve Jordan, who co-produced the LP.
   ``At the time I was going to write it, I just dried up. It was
frustrating me,'' he said.
   ``Steve said to me, `When in doubt, write about Mick.' He's hurt
me a lot and I just had to get it out. It's not entirely about
Mick. It's about anybody that gets disappointed about a friend and
has to let it out. It's a weird mixture of roughness and melody.''
   Richards played ``You Don't Move Me'' for Jagger, who he said
talked all the way through it. But Richards thinks the song will
eventually sink in.
   ``After these interviews, he's probably going to go to a room
and listen to it. He'll make this a mirror for him instead of just
having a mirror for him to look into.''
   Jagger and Richards have known each for nearly 40 years, living
in the same British neighborhood of Dartford for a while as
children, and forming a lasting friendship as teen-agers based on
their mutual interest in blues and rock 'n' roll.
   As Richards tells it, they met on a train around 1960 with
Jagger carrying a pile of blues albums under his arm. Richards was
already playing guitar and Jagger was doing some singing, so they
promptly began rehearsing together.
   They met up with another guitarist, Brian Jones, and shared a
flat in London, starving as Richards recalls, and playing music.
They auditioned for a bassist and decided on Bill Wyman, chosen at
the time more for the large amplifier he owned than for his playing.
   Drummer Charlie Watts, who had played with Jagger in a blues
group, joined the Stones in 1963.
   The Stones began, in Richards' words, as ``young missionaries,''
determined to bring blues music to a mass audience. Their name was
taken from a Muddy Waters song and much of their early material
were covers of blues and soul classics.
   In 1965, ``The Last Time,'' became their first self-written
single to reach the Top 10. Then came, ``Satisfaction,'' No. 1 in
England and the United States and still the Stones' most famous
song.
   They had the best of both worlds for a while. Critics loved the
Stones, naming them ``The World's Greatest Rock 'n' Roll Band.''
The fans loved them, not just for their music, but their
belligerent attitude.
   That attitude came at a price. In 1967, Jagger and Richards were
arrested for drugs and briefly jailed. Although the charges were
minor, Jagger for possession of four amphetamine tablets and
Richards for allowing marijuana to be used on his premises, both
were given lengthy sentences and the group's future was in doubt.
   After a public outcry, they were released and the Stones bounced
back in 1968 with the single ``Jumpin' Jack Flash,'' and the album
``Beggar's Banquet.''
   Jones, however, was suffering from the strain of repeated drug
busts and losing his girlfriend, Anita Pallenberg, to Richards. He
made only a minor contribution to ``Beggar's Banquet,'' and in June
of 1969, announced he was leaving the Stones because of ``musical''
differences. He was found dead in his swimming pool a month later.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1402EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Richards ADV11-13 1stAdd 10-31 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Richards, ADV 11-13, 1st Add,0732</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 11-13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: a month later.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mick Taylor, a 20-year-old blues guitarist, replaced Jones and
played on some of the Stones' greatest albums: ``Let It Bleed,''
``Sticky Fingers'' and Exiles on Main Street.'' He left the group
in 1974 and his replacement, Ron Wood, is still with the band.
   Wyman once noted that the Stones had always been able to
understand their own abilities and limitations. Jagger was the
singer, Jagger and Richards (and occasionally Wood) the
songwriters, Wyman the bass player and Watts the drummer.
   Unlike their onetime rivals, the Beatles, the Rolling Stones had
each accepted their roles. But Richards sees Jagger's concentration
on his solo career as a departure from that way of thinking.
   ``Mick and I used to pride ourselves on watching these new bands
screw up and make these obvious mistakes. Now it's happened to
us,'' he said.
   What happened was not just Jagger's recording of two solo
albums, but his refusal to tour behind the Stones' most recent LP,
1986's ``Dirty Work.''
   ``I made the record to go on the road and suddenly the rug was
pulled out from under that,'' Richards said. ``He took the Stones
for granted and thought he could just hire another Stones around
the corner.''
   Richards once brushed off the idea of making a solo album,
believing that ``bands splintering up for individual members to
record their own stuff is pointless.'' Why the change of heart?
   ``Because if I don't work I go mad,'' he said. ``At least I fear
I'd go mad. Also, over the last couple of years I found the people
I wanted to work with. People kept asking me to do it.''
   Richards makes no claim to being a `natural' singer, although he
was a soprano in the choir at Westminster Abbey and the Festival
Royal Hall for three years. ``My voice broke and that was that. My
career has gone downhill ever since,'' he said.
   But he has a way of putting across a song.
   Richards has a generous supply of friends on hand for ``Talk is
Cheap'': bassist Bootsy Collins and keyboardist Bernie Worrell of
Parliament-Funkadelic fame, producer Willie Mitchell and the
Memphis Horns, session guitarist Waddy Wachtel and many others.
   Mick Taylor is also on the record, playing on ``I Could Have
Stood You Up,'' a song that shows Chuck Berry's influence on
Richards. Berry's longtime keyboardist, Johnny Johnson, plays on
the cut.
   Richards met Johnson during ``Hail! Hail! Rock 'n' Roll,'' the
critically acclaimed concert film on Berry.
   It's been 30 years since Richards first heard Berry and became
his most famous fan. The Rolling Stones' first single was a cover
of Berry's ``Come On.'' The Stones also recorded ``Carol,'' ``Let
it Rock,'' ``Around and Around'' and several other Berry songs.
Originals such as ``Brown Sugar'' and ``Star Star'' are openly
patterned after Berry's music.
   Richards said exposing Berry and other black artists to white
audiences was the primary reason the Stones were formed.
   ``We were idealistic,'' he said. ``The initial reason for
putting the band together was not to make the Rolling Stones stars.
We just wanted to turn people on to Muddy Waters and Jimmy Reed. We
figured if we could play stuff good enough then other people would
want to know where we got it.''
   Ironically, the Stones developed a sound so distinctive that
listeners were often unaware where such songs as ``Time Is on My
Side'' and ``It's All Over Now'' came from.
   But now the Stones are struggling to continue. The early
obstacles no longer exist: They no longer have the Beatles to
compete with; their days as rock's ``bad boys'' are long gone.
   ``It can certainly be pulled back together,'' Richards said.
``The positive side is the stuff I've learned the last two years _
just having that breather, some fresh air.''
   Wood has favored a reunion all along. Wyman has suggested the
group call it quits. Jagger, struggling with his solo career, has
said he'd like to record with the Stones again. Watts has left it
for the others to decide.
   Richards is optimistic: He sees another Stones album coming out
in 1989.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 11-13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1459EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Allende ADV11-13   10-31 1048</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Allende, ADV 11-13,1079</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov 11-13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: The Story of a Storyteller</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isabel Allende is a storyteller. ``Eva Luna,''
her third novel, is the story of a storyteller.
   ``I come from a long order of tradition,'' Allende said in a
recent interview. ``I used to listen to the maid and cook tell
stories in the kitchen. I loved that. I've read stories since I was
very little. I grew up with storytelling.''
   ``Eva Luna'' (Knopf, $18.95) takes place in a Latin American
country closely resembling Chile. The title character is orphaned
as a child and grows up poor, working as a domestic. But she soon
discovers she can earn a living by telling stories.
   ``I never realized it was something that I had and that I could
trade for something else,'' Allende said. ``Like Eva Luna, I
realized when I was 40 that I had been trading stories for other
goods and making a living of it.''
   Storytelling, the author explained, is a way of preserving
memory. Since leaving Chile after the 1973 military coup, she has
struggled to remember the environment that shaped her as a child.
   ``I realized about myself that I have lost something that was
invisible, that I could not put in words,'' said Allende, who
became a resident of Caracas, Venezuela. ``The only word I could
think of was roots. It's memory.''
   And what Allende misses goes beyond specific sights and sounds.
Living in a foreign country, she struggles for a sense of identity.
   ``If you walk in your own city, in your own country with your
people, you hear the language of your own country. You have the
feeling that somehow you know the subtle rules and you know how to
get along.
   ``When you're taken away from that, you don't belong anywhere.
You're all by yourself, you have no roots and the memory of the
past starts fading away.''
   So Allende uses her stories to keep the past alive.
   ``I have the feeling I have lost my family, my country, my
friends, the accent of my own language,'' she said. ``But very
specifically, the memory _ something that had been with me
naturally. Now I'm reconstructing every day. Now it's finally mine,
it's printed, portable. I can take it with me.''
   Allende, whose father was a diplomat, was born in 1942 in Lima,
Peru, but moved to Santiago, Chile, at the age of 3. She lived
comfortably as a child and was spared the poverty under which so
many in her country lived.
   ``I grew up in a world on contrasts _ extreme wealth and extreme
poverty,'' she said. ``I belonged to the bubble. That means I've
been fortunate, but I was also aware of that inequality. Though I
was always touched by that, I never came to terms with it until the
military coup.''
   She married an engineer when she was 19 and had two children.
She supported the government of Salvador Allende, a Socialist
elected president in 1970. (The author says she's a distant
cousin). He was overthrown by the military in 1973 and executed.
After Gen. Augusto Pinochet took over and declared a state of
emergency, he tortured and murdered political opponents and
censored the press.
   Allende, a journalist at the time, recalled the day of the coup:
``I left my house very early in the morning and I went to my job. I
saw only soldiers passing in tanks and airplanes and everybody
hiding in their homes. I saw the bombing of the (President's)
palace. That very day, I had the feeling my whole life was
changing.''
   She was an outspoken opponent of the regime and went into exile
in 1975, leaving her family behind. They were later reunited.
   ``When I learned I could be taken into prison with my children
and have them tortured in front of me, it became unbearable. I had
to leave,'' she said.
   Her first novel, ``House of the Spirits,'' was released in 1982
and combined her strong political beliefs with ``magic realism,'' a
writing style associated with such Latin American writers as
Gabriel Garcia Marquez.
   ``You can not be an artist for the sake of art only in Latin
America,'' she said. ``I would say the same goes for any country in
the world where there is great repression and violence.''
   Magic is also essential. Allende writes in Eva Luna:
   ``I was writing a new episode every day, totally immersed in the
world. I was creating with the all-encompassing power of words,
transformed into a multifaceted being, reproduced to infinity,
seeing my own reflection in multiple mirrors, living countless
lives, speaking with many voices.''
   And magic also is part of her roots: ``It's a combination of
legends, superstitions, myths. The Indian culture, the African
culture. The dreams of the Spaniards who came here. The possibility
of finding Utopia.''
   Allende's second novel, ``Of Love and Shadows,'' came out in
1987, and had the same themes of good and evil, darkness and light,
that appear in all her works.
   She balances Eva Luna's passionate love affairs with the
violence and oppression of the outside world.
   ``I think that I'm surrounded by violence, shadows, confusion,''
the author said. ``Writing is maybe a naive attempt to make the
world more comprehensible, more tolerable.
   ``Shadows for me are all those things that are threatening and
have always been there, are still there. Death, repression, abuse,
inequality, mystery _ things in which I'm immersed, constantly.''
   Allende is divorced from her first husband and recently married
a San Francisco lawyer. With Chileans rejecting the presidency of
Pinochet in a recent plebescite, she will visit the country in
December.
   ``I froze a country 15 years ago and took it with me,'' she
said. ``When I go back, I won't know where I'll belong. Who will be
my friend when I go back?''
   But no matter what, Allende will go on telling stories.
   ``Eva Luna can not only trade the stories, she can make her life
better and others around her. She makes the world more tolerable.
That's what I try to do all the time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 11-13</NOTE>
</DOC>
