<DOCNO> AP881031-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 0210EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Holidays:WithToys-Children     10-31 0108</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Holidays: With Toys-Children,0108</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holidays: With Toys-Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the worst toys for children are the expensive gimmicky
spectator type, such as talking dolls and bears because they do
things as the child watches passively, according to Jack Lochhead
of the University of Massachusetts at Amherst.
   Such toys squelch the child's imagination and limit play,
explains Lochhead, director of the university's Center for
Cognitive Research Processes.
   The best toys, he says, are low cost, low tech toys that offer
imaginative play _ unpainted wooden blocks that help teach
geometric patterns and mathematical concepts and the educational
toys often found in schools.
</TEXT>
