<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Holidays:ToyBriefs     10-31 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Holidays: Toy Briefs,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holidays: Toy Briefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Interactive, high-tech action games are the trend of the
'80s,'' says David Galoob, president of Lewis Galoob Toys.
   The company introduced Flashball, a battery-powered electronic
paddle game, at the 1988 Toy Fair.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Kenner Products and Those Characters from Cleveland have
introduced a Special Blessings line of praying dolls.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   High finance is the theme in new board games called Greed, from
the Avalon Hill Game Co., and Wall Street Raiders, from
Developmental Games Inc.
   ESM Marketing has introduced It's Only Money, a board game
featuring a shopping mall ``occupied'' by the names and logos of 25
real companies _ and a real prize of $400,000 for players (a
$300,000 condominium at the World of Venetia in Miami, and a
$100,000 shopping spree). An entry form is in each box.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   An unusual board game is designed to help ease children's
adjustment to divorce.
   Created by two certified social workers with extensive
experience working with divorced families, the game _ called
``Divorce Cope'' _ is designed for children age 8 and up to play
with parents, grandparents and other family members, or with family
therapists, guidance counselors, social workers and other
professionals.
   The game is distributed by Theraplay Inc., of Monsey, N.Y.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Random House Inc., which also publishes the Random House
Dictionary, suggests spelling sdrowkcab _ with a new board game
called Backwords. Three to eight players try to guess words that
are pronounced backwards in order to move around the board and
reach the University of Reversity.
   Lewis Galoob Toys is also backwards in its approach, with
Babble, a battery-powered electronic listening game that repeats
words backwards.
   A similar reverse direction is apparent in Parker Brothers' Mad
Magazine game, in which players roll the dice with their left hand
and move counter-clockwise in an attempt to lose their money to win.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Applause, Inc., in a merchandising arrangement with Steven
Spielberg and Universal Studios, has introduced E.T. plush and
figurine dolls. The popular creature is from Spielberg's movie,
``E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A Parker Brothers board game called Willow is based on the
George Lucas movie of that name and features fairies, brownies,
death dogs, a wise sorcerer and a wicked sorceress, heroes and
villains.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The California raisins made popular in television commercials
provide the inspiration for a new board game for children, from
Decipher Inc., as well as a wind-up toy, an AM-FM radio and a
wireless microphone, from Nasta Industries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A Lego Systems brick robot ``chews'' spaghetti and spews the
bits of ``pasta'' onto a trolley that rolls out on rails from its
back. It also walks, turns, carries things in its hands and flashes
its eyes after a meal.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   All of the wooden toys from Westport Products, a division of
Goodwill Industries, Muskegon, Mich., are manufactured, assembled
and packaged by handicapped and disadvantaged people in a joint
venture project with a workshop for the disabled in Heidenheim,
West Germany.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The record for playing the card game Uno, according to its
International Games distributors, goes to a group of villagers in
Forssa, Finland, who played nonstop for six days (144 hours) in
December 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Barbie and Ken dolls, manufactured by Mattel, were named
after the children of the dolls' inventors, Ruth and Elliot
Handler. Mattel says it sells more than 20 million Barbie fashions
annually, with her wedding gown the most popular.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
