<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Holidays:Firing     10-31 0134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Holidays: Firing,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holidays: Firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Is firing people during the holidays cruel or kind, and could
this actually be an opportune time to be out of work?
   According to Stephen Strasser, associate professor of management
and human resources at Ohio State University, there is no good time
to get laid off from work.
   But a holiday firing can present natural opportunities to
network, says Strasser, author of ``Working It Out: Sanity and
Success in the Workplace.''
   ``People are usually very supportive and sympathetic,'' he says,
``because we all easily identify with the individual who has been
fired.''
   Strasser adds that holidays can be a good time for job hunting
because ``many companies review their budgets and staff changes
often are made at the first of the year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
