<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0454</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. said it agreed to a $13.1 billion
buyout by Philip Morris Cos. Inc., apparently ending a short but
intense hostile takeover fight in the biggest merger ever between
two non-oil U.S. companies.
   In a joint statement, the two food giants said Sunday they
reached a definitive agreement in which Philip Morris would boost
its outstanding $90 a share tender offer to $106 for each of
Kraft's outstanding shares.
   The merger would make Philip Morris the world's biggest maker of
consumer goods, displacing the British-Dutch company Unilever NV.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. accused RJR
Nabisco Inc.'s managers of trying to sell pieces of the
food-tobacco giant, which would make it less attractive in the face
of the investment firm's $20.3 billion offer.
   The accusations were contained in a letter Kohlberg Kravis sent
to RJR Nabisco's committee of outside directors and appeared to
heighten the antagonism building in the biggest corporate takeover
ever proposed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said the federal budget
deficit, after dramatically improving last year, grew in fiscal
1988 to $155.1 billion.
   The Reagan administration's final accounting for the budget year
that ended Sept. 30, issued Friday, showed the imbalance between
revenue and spending rose $5.4 billion, or 3.6 percent, from $149.7
billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the first test of a tough new trade law,
the Reagan administration rejected a request from U.S. rice farmers
that it investigate whether Japan unfairly blocks imports.
   The announcement Friday by U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter was surprising because because supporters of the request
were hoping the pressure of presidential politics would force a
different outcome.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Occupational Safety and Health
Administration slapped a record $4.33 million fine on John Morrell
& Co., saying the meatpacker forced hundreds of injured employees
to work even immediately after surgery.
   The fine, leveled Friday, reflected what Assistant Labor
Secretary John A. Pendergrass called ``an employer who knew about a
serious health hazard, saw the tragic toll on its workers and chose
to ignore it.'' Morrell said it would fight the fine in court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Telephone & Telegraph Co. won a
spirited competition to provide thousands of new computers to the
Defense Department, establishing its position in the industry for
years to come with what has been described as the computer contract
of the century.
   The contract awarded Friday was worth $929.1 million, and AT&T
officials said it could ultimately exceed $1 billion depending on
options excercised.
</TEXT>
