<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawn darts could be removed from the nation's
store shelves before Christmas under a ban voted by the federal
Consumer Product Safety Commission.
   In addition to that action Friday, the safety agency voted to
extend indefinitely a ban on the sale of three-wheel all-terrain
vehicles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's total trade surplus dipped 10.6 percent in
September from a year earlier to $7.605 billion, the Finance
Ministry announced.
   Ministry officials said Friday the year-to-year decline in the
surplus was caused by growth of imports, particularly of
manufactured goods. But they said demand continued to grow overseas
for Japanese exports such as semiconductors, video tape recorders,
televisions and office equipment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners, which launched a tender offer
to acquire food service giant TW Services Inc., said it would sell
the company's small health services operations if the deal succeeds.
   The aggressive investment firm also said Friday Citibank has
agreed to provide $750 million to finance what would be a $1.14
billion acquisition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has asked Asian nations
to help investigate reports of widespread illegal salmon fishing in
the North Pacific.
   The government's action, disclosed Friday, came after American
fishing groups claimed the Taiwanese, Japanese and perhaps South
Koreans are catching the salmon under the guise of fishing for
squid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Milken, Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc.'s high-yield bond chief who's at the center of a federal
insider-trading probe, says the ordeal of the nearly 2-year-old
investigation has taken a personal toll.
   Milken spoke in a rare interview published Friday in The
Trentonian newspaper, which is owned by Ingersoll Publications Co.
The company's chief executive, Ralph Ingersoll, is a personal
friend of Milken's and a Drexel client.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose modestly Friday in slow trading, partly
recouping losses of the previous session. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials rose 9.06 to 2,149.89 but still showed a 33.61
weekly loss.
   Bond prices ended higher in light trading. The Treasury's
30-year bond climbed about $2.80 for every $1,000 in face value and
its yield eased to 8.80 percent from 8.83 percent late Thursday.
   Elsewhere, the dollar fell in light trading, precious metals
rose, energy futures were mostly higher and other commodities were
mixed.
</TEXT>
