<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 0758EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-31 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen today
despite intervention by the Bank of Japan, while share prices rose
slightly on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 125.00 yen, down 1.08 yen from Friday's
finish at 126.08 yen. Opening at 125.72 yen, the currency fell and
ranged from 124.98-125.85 yen.
   ``The central bank intervened a few times, but it didn't work,''
said Michiko Kawai, a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   A Bank of Japan official refused to say if it had intervened to
try to keep the dollar from falling.
   ``We know nothing about it. We don't give out any information
about our activities,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Exchange dealers said the dollar opened low mainly due to a
decline in the currency on overseas markets. They said investors'
generally felt the U.S. economy was slowing down and that was
driving the dollar down.
   Kawai said the dollar-selling mood was still strong in the
market.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 219.67-point winner
Saturday, gained 21.53 more points, or 0.08 percent, to end at
27,982.54. The market has risen six straight days starting last
Tuesday.
   The Nikkei topped the 28,000 level at mid-morning today for the
first time since Sept. 19, when Emperor Hirohito fell seriously ill.
   But profit-taking and fears about the continued rise in share
prices over the last five trading days gradually pressed the Nikkei
back below the 28,000-point level toward the end of the trading,
dealers said.
   In a moderate trading with volume on the first section estimated
at $1.1 billion, food, drugs and paper issues attracted investors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0315 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 0920EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NECPlant     10-31 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NEC Plant,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEC Conducting Feasibility Study For 4-Megabit U.S. Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NEC Corp., the world's largest semiconductor maker,
said Monday it was conducting a study to determine the feasibility
of producing 4-megabit dynamic random-access memories, known as
DRAMs, in the United States.
   NEC spokesman Hisashi Saito said his company ``will reach a
decision on the project sometime around next April or May, based on
the results of an ongoing feasibility study.''
   A 4-megabit DRAM, said to be the next-generation computer memory
chip, has four times the memory capacity of a 1-megabit DRAM, the
most advanced computer chip currently being mass-produced.
   Saito said his company plans to send commercial samples of the
4-megabit DRAMs to the United States next month, even though the
chips are not yet available on the Japanese market.
   No other Japanese makers have yet launched the production of
4-megabit DRAMs commercially.
   Presently, 1-megabit DRAMs are used in mainframe computers,
high-performance work stations and other electronics equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
