<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     10-31 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0221</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened lower today in
featureless trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 8.71 points at
2,141.18 after a half-hour of trading at 10 a.m. EST.
   Analysts said the market was drifting, after reacting sharply
last week to a frenzy of corporate takeover attempts.
   ``There's nothing around to stimulate it,'' said Larry Wachtel,
an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``There's all kinds
of incentives to sit around on one's rear end and await
developments.''
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 23.54 million shares.
   Declining issues outpaced advancing ones by around 2 to 1 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 597 issues falling, 302 gaining and
491 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks had
slipped 0.35 to 156.44.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.78 at 300.97.
   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 9.06 to
2,149.89, reducing its loss for the week to 33.61 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 853 up, 580 down and 514 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 146.30 million shares, down from 196.54
million in last Thursday's session.
</TEXT>
