<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade with the soybean market
leading the way on a combination of technical buy signals and
indications of stronger export demand.
   Analysts said professionals who watch trends on price charts had
turned bullish on the soybean market following Friday's late rally,
which appeared to mark a turnaround in the market's direction.
   Most of the news last week was bearish for beans and ``when a
market stops going down on negative news, it's always a sign to
technicians that we've just about sold off enough, at least for the
near term,'' said Richard Feltes, director of commodities research
with Refco Inc., a Chicago-based commodities brokerage.
   Feltes also said a large foreign grain company was positioned to
take delivery of a large amount of soybeans, which the market saw
as a positive sign on the export sales front.
   In early trading, wheat was 2} cents to 4{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.14 a bushel; corn was \
cent lower to 2 cents higher with December at $2.80} a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.36 a bushel;
and soybeans were 4 cents lower to 7 cents higher with November at
$7.75 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were most lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .22 cent lower with December at
73.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with November at 81.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .25
cent lower to .08 cent higher with December at 40.95 cents a pound;
and frozen pork bellies were .65 cent lower to .03 cent higher with
February at 46.25 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on Friday while pork futures
were mixed.
</TEXT>
