<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chrysler-H-Cars     10-31 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chrysler-H-Cars,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ward's: Chrysler to End LeBaron Production in March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will end production of its
Chrysler LeBaron GTS and Dodge Lancer automobiles in March because
of slumping sales, an automotive newsletter said Monday.
   Ward's Automotive Reports said halting production of the models,
called H-cars by Chrysler, will result in a few layoffs at the
company's Sterling Heights, Mich. plant.
   Chrysler spokesman Doug Nicoll said Monday he had no comment on
future production or product plans.
   The Sterling Heights factory also makes the Dodge Shadow and the
Plymouth Sundance, which require less labor time to assemble than
the Lancer-LeBaron GTS models. The Sterling Heights plant will
shift to making just the Shadow and Sundance models, Ward's said,
quoting plant sources.
   Nicoll said the Shadow-Sundance cars account for 92 percent of
the cars coming off the assembly line at the Sterling Heights
plant, the rest being LeBaron GTS and Lancer models.
   Through September of this year, Ward's said, LeBaron GTS sales
have slipped to 13,000 from 25,000 a year ago, a 48 percent
decline. Lancer sales have dropped to 9,000 in the
January-September period this year from 19,000 during the same time
last year, a 52.6 percent decline.
   The newsletter also said that the LeBaron and Lancer may be
reintroduced in the 1993 model year on the ``LH'' platform and be
assembled at the company's expanded Jefferson Avenue plant in
Detroit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
