<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Westinghouse     10-31 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Westinghouse,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Software Venture Set</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. said Monday it
will join with Multiflow Computer Inc. to market computer programs
for engineers.
   The engineering service bureau of Westinghouse will provide
programs and computer systems for analyzing electricity, magnetism,
heat and other areas in the realm called finite element analysis.
   Multiflow, based in Branford, Conn., is a leader in its field of
computer technology and is a leader in high performance computers
for science, engineering and general applications.
   ``At one time, a multi-million dollar supercomputer was the only
practical machine for solving a large class of sophisticated finite
element analysis problems,'' said Joe Santoro, a manager in
Westinghouse's nuclear and advanced technology division.
   ``Today, high-performance machines ... are bringing this
computing power within the reach of hundreds of engineering
organizations. Our approach with Multiflow is to provide an
economical hardware and software package for those organizations
that require near-supercomputer performance at a fraction of the
cost,'' he said.
</TEXT>
