<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tacoma Officials Back WPPSS Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tacoma officials today approved a proposed
$221 million settlement in the Washington Public Power Supply
System securities fraud case, and Gov. Booth Gardner recommended
that the state pay $10 million toward the settlement.
   The settlement, subject to approval by 13 other utilities, was
proposed by bondholders' lawyers to resolve a case inspired by the
largest municipal bond default in history.
   The only utility that would remain as a defendant would be
Snohomish County Public Utility District, which contracted for the
biggest share, 13 percent, on two WPPSS nuclear power plants.
   The trial was recessed last week in Tucson, Ariz., when
attorneys reported a settlement was possible. It is scheduled to
resume Wednesday.
   Construction was halted on two WPPSS nuclear plants in 1982 and
WPPSS later defaulted on the $2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance
construction of the plants, precipitating a flood of lawsuits.
   A class of more than 24,000 past and present bondholders and
Chemical Bank of New York, a trustee for bondholders, claim the
defendants conspired to lie and hide information that might have
discouraged potential investors.
   In a resolution from the Tacoma City Council and the city
utilities board, Tacoma agreed to pay $40.2 million as its share of
the settlement.
   Ted Coates, Tacoma City Light's director of utilities, said the
agreement was also contingent on federal approval of a $35 million
payment from the Bonneville Power Administration.
   Bonneville, which backed financing of WPPSS's three other
nuclear power plants, markets power from federal dams in the
Northwest, and is the region's largest power broker with an annual
budget of $3 billion.
   In Olympia, Gardner and Attorney General Ken Eikenberry today
recommended that the state contribute $10 million in a lawsuit
settlement.
   ``We believe that this will finally put the WPPSS issue behind
us,'' Gardner and Eikenberry said in a letter to state legislators.
   Washington state is not a defendant in the case on trial, but a
settlement should end a separate lawsuit against the state
involving the same plaintiffs, who are suing to recover $7.5
billion _ the $2.3 billion default plus interest.
   The proposed state involvement in the case would require
approval of the Legislature. Gardner and Eikenberry said they would
ask for an appropriation in the supplemental budget when the
lawmakers convene next January.
   The 13 other public utility districts involved in the settlement
proposed by the bondholders were expected to vote soon on the
proposal.
   Besides the utilities, remaining defendants include two
engineering firms and a financial consulting firm. There has been
no talk of settlement involving the professional firms, and
attorneys with two of the firms said last week that no talks were
going on involving their clients.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
