<DOCNO> AP881031-0330 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Scotus-MiddleSouth     10-31 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus-Middle South,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockholder Suit Against Middle South Sent Back To Trial Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court upheld on Monday an
appeals court decision reviving a suit by stockholders who claim
Middle South Utilities Inc. hid its shaky financial condition to
inflate the value of its stock.
   The high court refused without comment to hear an appeal of a
decision by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that a federal
district judge dismissed the lawsuit without sufficient explanation.
   The 5th Circuit's ruling in June said that if U.S. District
Judge Adrian Duplantier again dismisses the suit, he must explain
why in detail so that appeal courts have something on which to base
their review.
   Spokesman Cyril Guerrera said Middle South did not have any
immediate comment on the Supreme Court's action.
   Middle South, based in New Orleans, is an electric utility
holding company that owns Louisiana Power & Light Co., New Orleans
Power & Light Co., Mississippi Power & Light Co. and Arkansas Power
& Light Co. A fifth subsidiary, Systems Energy Resources Inc., runs
Grand Gulf _ a nuclear power plant in Mississippi which sells power
to all four utilities.
   The company has been beset by money troubles for years because
of Grand Gulf, though it announced last month that it would pay its
first quarterly dividend since July 1985.
   Rita Isquith and other stockholders filed suit in August 1985.
Middle South announced the following month that it was near
bankruptcy and that _ for the first time in its 36-year history _
it would not be paying dividends on common stock.
   The lawsuits claimed that Middle South deliberately withheld
information from investors about its deteriorating financial
condition. The stockholders said they were suing on behalf of
anyone who bought stock between Dec. 7, 1982, and Aug. 16, 1985, a
period of heavy trading.
   The company's troubles center on its $6 billion investment in
nuclear power. In addition to Grand Gulf, near Port Gibson, Miss.,
LP&L owns Waterford 3 near Taft, La., about 20 miles up the
Mississippi River from New Orleans.
   There were huge cost overruns and repeated construction delays
in building both plants; Middle South has said it does not expect
to complete a second Grand Gulf plant.
   Middle South has obtained rate increases for the two working
plants, but stockholders have had to absorb some of the plants'
costs as part of the deals cut with regulators.
</TEXT>
