<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mostly higher Monday in foreign
exchange trading in Europe, as reported intervention by the U.S.
Federal Reserve and the Bank of Japan lifted the dollar above its
lows.
   Gold prices also rose.
   Dealers said the dollar fell on low volume in Tokyo, despite
reports that the Bank of Japan intervened to push the dollar higher.
   Reports that the Fed bought dollars for yen twice during the
European day pushed the dollar to its session highs before it
drifted back.
   Dealers said the intervention succeeded in supporting the dollar
for the day, but they said bearish sentiment toward the dollar is
widespread.
   Several dealers said they felt the Fed intervened on behalf of
the Japanese central bank, and felt the intervention was not meant
to turn market sentiment around.
   ``The intervention may be enough to steady the market for the
week,'' said Steve Barrow, corporate advisor at Chemical Bank,
``but it wasn't enough to turn around market sentiment.''
   Bearish sentiment stems from disappointment that the U.S. trade
deficit has not shown enough signs of improvement, while slower
U.S. economic growth has disappointed those looking for higher U.S.
interest rates, dealers said.
   Dealers said the dollar's movement Monday was accentuated by a
thin market, since many corporate players have moved to the
sidelines before the U.S. presdential elections next week, while
markets in France, the Philippines, Taiwan and Ireland were closed
Monday for a holiday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 1.08 Japanese yen to a closing 125.00 yen.
Later in London, it rose slightly to 125.45 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7678 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7680 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Friday, included: 1.7810 West German marks, up from 1.7755; 1.4995
Swiss francs, up from 1.4970; 6.0800 French francs, up from 6.0750;
2.0000 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0010; 1,320.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,321.50; and 1.2204 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2035.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $411.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $410.50 an ounce late Friday. In Zurich, gold rose to
$412.25 an ounce compared with $411.25 late Friday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose 18 cents to close at $414.46 a
troy ounce.
   Silver bullion prices held steady on the London market where the
metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.31 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
