<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1728EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ConstructionContracting     10-31 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Contracting,0372</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Decline in Commercial Building Pushes Down New Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New construction contracting fell 3 percent in
September, pulled down by a decline in commerical and industrial
projects, a business research concern reported Monday.
   It was the third consecutive monthly decline in total new
construction starts, now valued at $238 billion on an annualized
basis, according to the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information
Services Co.
   All of the latest month's decline was concentrated in commercial
and industrial projects, the report said.
   George A. Christie, a McGraw-Hill economist, said continuing
vacancies in commercial buildings and an overall reduction in
public spending had reversed a five-year expansion of building
activity. Christie predicted the downward trend in new contracting
would continue.
   ``Newly started construction is on its way to a 3 percent
decline in 1988, with the prospect of a further dip next year,'' he
said.
   Christie said a seasonally adjusted 7 percent dip in
non-residential building in September seemed inconsistent with
1988's surge of manufacturing.
   Market fundamentals indicate industrial plant construction
should be up sharply, given a capacity utilization of 84 percent in
the nation's factories, he said.
   ``Instead, contracting so far in 1988 is running 10 percent
behind last year,'' he said.
   Residential construction, meanwhile, remained at an annual rate
of $115.7 billion in September, unchanged from the previous month,
due in part to relatively stable mortgage interest rates.
   The value of contracts for non-building construction, such as
public works and utilities, increased 1 percent to an annualized
rate of $40.1 billion last month, the report said. An increase in
highway and other public works construction was partially offset by
a decline in utility projects.
   For the first nine months, new construction starts on an
unadjusted basis totaled $191.7 billion, down 3 percent from the
same period in 1987.
   The South has remained the weakest building sector in 1988, with
6 percent fewer construction starts than in 1987. The northeastern
and north-central areas of the United States also showed declines,
of 1 percent and 2 percent, respectivetly. Building in the nation's
western region remained unchanged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0336 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1737EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Boeing     10-31 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Boeing,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Earnings Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. said Monday its third-quarter
profit climbed 38.5 percent on a 4.5 percent increase in revenue.
   The aerospace concern said it earned $144 million, or 94 cents a
share, in the third quarter compared with $104 million, or 67 cents
a share, in tne same period a year earlier.
   Third-quarter sales rose to $3.72 billion from $3.56 billion in
the third quarter of 1987.
   For the nine months ended Sept. 30, Boeing reported it earned
$440 million, or $2.88 per share, up 29.8 percent from $339
million, or $2.18 per share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month sales rose 11 percent to $12.1 billion from $10.9
billion a year earlier.
   Boeing attributed the improved earnings to higher sales volume,
lower levels of research, development and other new-business
expenses, lower federal income-tax rates and increased income from
other sources.
   Those items were partially offset by ``significant performance
problems on several military aircraft programs,'' increased costs
associated with commuter aircraft, and increased ``cost-share
expenditures on government contracts.''
   During the third quarter, 24 customers announced orders for 100
jet transports and 10 de Havilland turboprop commuter planes valued
at $5.1 billion, Boeing said, compared with $3.8 billion in orders
last year.
   For the first nine months of the year, 497 jetliners and 45
turboprop aircraft were ordered, valued at $23.1 billion. That
compares with 267 jetliners and 40 turboprops, valued at $14.9
billion, in the first three quarters of 1987, Boeing said.
   Through Monday, Boeing's total announced 1988 orders stand at a
record 560 jetliners, valued at about $25.8 billion. The latest
order, also announced Monday, was Royal Air Maroc's for 10 737
jetliners and options on 10 more.
</TEXT>
