<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1913EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Shingles-Tariffs     10-31 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shingles-Tariffs,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Urge Reagan To Continue Tariff on Canadian Shingles,
Shakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen Northwest lawmakers urged President
Reagan on Monday to maintain tariffs on cedar shakes and shingles
imported from Canada imposed almost 30 months ago.
   The lawmakers, in a letter to Reagan, said that dropping the
duty rather than proceeding with plans to gradually phase it out
``would result in shake and shingle prices plummeting as Canadian
imports pour in.
   ``We are confident that if relief (for the domestic industry) is
continued for the full five-year period as you announced in May
1986, the industry will be able to meet Canadian competition head
on without additional government assistance.''
   In announcing the tariffs, Reagan has said they were necessary
to allow the industry, mostly based in Washington state and Oregon,
to adjust to competition by modernizing mills and developing
alternatives to traditional cedar shakes and shingles.
   The administration imposed a five-year program that called for a
35 percent tariff during the first 30 months, a 20 percent tariff
between 30 months and 54 months and an 8 percent tariff for the
final six months.
   Reagan said it was his ``intention'' to maintain the tariffs for
the entire period ``if general market conditions continue to
warrant relief and if the domestic producers have begun to make
reasonable progress toward adjustment during the first 30-month
period.''
   But Reagan also asked the International Trade Commission to
report to him on the ``probable economic effect'' on the domestic
shake and shingle industry if all tariffs were removed after 30
months.
   The commission in early October was unable to reach agreement on
whether to recommend a continuation of the tariff program as
planned, with three commissioners voting to drop all tariffs
immediately and three supporting thegradual phaseout originally
envisioned.
   The lawmakers warned that unless the tariffs were maintained as
planned ``it will cause extreme hardship on the industry.''
   Many mill owners have purchased or ordered timber in
anticipation of the continuation of the tariffs and thus have no
way to reduce their costs to compete against cheaper Canadian
products if the tariffs were dropped, the lawmakers said.
   Since the tariffs were imposed, the lawmakers said the Canadian
share of the market has dropped from 73 percent to 59 percent,
employment in the domestic industry is up 26 percent, wages up 39
percent, production up 41 percent and mill productivity up 12
percent.
   The letter was signed by Democratic Reps. Don Bonker, Al Swift
and Mike Lowry of Washington state, Les AuCoin and Peter DeFazio of
Oregon and Richard Stallings of Idaho.
   Republican House members signing the letter were John Miller of
Washington state, Denny Smith and Bob Smith of Oregon and Larry
Craig of Idaho.
   Senators signing the letter were Democrat Brock Adams of
Washington state and Republicans James McClure and Steve Symms of
Idaho.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
