<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1845EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 3rdLd-Writethru   10-31 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0592</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 15th graf The NYSE's to CORRECT change and close to up
0.15 to 156.94.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted to a mostly lower
finish Monday in dull trading, as Wall Street recovered from last
week's takeover frenzy and waited for new developments.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 1.24 points to
2,148.65. The blue-chip indicator remained slightly lower through
most of the trading session.
   Declining issues edged out advances by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
835 issues down, 626 up and 496 unchanged.
   Stocks came under some pressure from an early decline in the
dollar, but mostly just slipped under their own weight, analysts
said.
   ``There's nothing around to stimulate it,'' said Larry Wachtel,
an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``There's all kinds
of incentives to sit around on one's rear end and await
developments.''
   Many participants were said to be sidelined, awaiting Tuesday's
meeting of the Federal Reserve's policymaking arm and U.S.
unemployment figures for October, scheduled for release on Friday.
The fast-approaching presidential election also has dampened
activity.
   Some observers expect the central bank's Federal Open Market
Committee _ meeting just a week before the election _ to decide to
keep credit policy and interest rates stable. Recent signs that
inflationary pressures are easing would make the Fed loathe to push
interest rates higher, and could even persuade it to lower them,
some analysts believe.
   ``The thinking is there will be no need to raise interest
rates,'' said Monte Gordon, an analyst for Dreyfus Corp.
   That view gained further credence Monday when Martha R. Seger, a
member of the Fed's Board of Governors, estimated that the nation's
economy has slowed in the third quarter and will grow by 1 percent
to 2 percent next year.
   Seger told the Economic Club of Detroit that recent economic
data have allayed fears of rekindled inflation.
   Stock prices got a brief boost in the afternoon from a rebound
in the dollar, market watchers said. The Fed came into the
foreign-exchange market at least twice Monday to bolster the dollar
by buying the U.S. currency and selling Japanese yen, according to
exchange dealers.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE totaled 143.46 million shares,
down slightly from 146.30 million in last Friday's session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 170.60 million shares.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, RJR Nabisco fell 1\ to
83}. The company is the object of a $20.3 billion bid from
investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. Sears Roebuck, which
announced a restructuring, lost 1~ at 41}, General Motors was down
{ at 83] and Mobil slipped [ to 44].
   Food giant Kraft, which agreed Sunday to be acquired by tobacco
company Philip Morris for $13.1 billion, soared 7 to 103{.
Pillsbury was up { at 60.
   The NYSE's composite index edged up 0.15 to 156.94.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 0.59 to 321.26, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 0.44 at 278.97.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index slipped
0.80 to 300.95.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
closed at 382.46, down 0.33.
   The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, the market value of NYSE,
American and OTC issues, rose by $2.75 billion.
</TEXT>
