<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Coca-ColaEnterprises     10-31 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coca-Cola Enterprises,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Enterprises Selling Bottler To Johnston</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises announced Monday it has
agreed to sell its Coca-Cola Bottling Co. of Mid-America, which
serves portions of seven Midwestern states, for about $285 million.
   Coca-Cola Enterprises said it had signed a letter of intent to
sell Mid-America to Johnston Coca-Cola Bottling Group Inc. of
Chattanooga, Tenn.
   Completion of the deal is expected by the end of the year,
according to a statement.
   The company being sold serves a territory that includes the
cities of Kansas City and Omaha and portions of Iowa, Missouri,
Kansas, Illinois, Wisconsin, Nebraska and Minnesota.
   Coca-Cola Enterprises said it expects the proposed sale to
result in a one-time gain of approximately $110 million before tax.
   In addition to the sale, Coca-Cola Enterprises announced Monday
a share repurchase program of up to 25 million shares of its common
stock.
   ``We have always stated that CCE would consider divesting
bottling companies as part of its overall net acquisition
strategy,'' said Brian G. Dyson, chief executive officer of
Coca-Cola Enterprises.
   ``We believe that the use of part of the proceeds of such a
divestiture in a share repurchase program is one of the ways we can
deliver value to our shareholders while implementing CCE's
corporate strategy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
