<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Stroh'sCooler     10-31 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stroh's Cooler,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stroh's To Bottle, Distribute California Cooler In The United
States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Stroh Companies Inc. and Brown-Forman Corp.
announced an agreement Monday under which the Detroit beermaker
will bottle and distribute California Cooler wine cooler in the
United States.
   Stroh planned to begin blending and bottling California Cooler
at several of its facilities by March 1989, when Brown-Forman was
to close its plant in Stockton, Calif., the companies said in a
statement.
   Brown-Forman planned to grant Stroh its exclusive license to
produce and market California Cooler in the U.S. within 60 days,
the statement said.
   But the Louisville, Ky.-based corporation would retain worldwide
ownership of the brand and would continue manufacturing and
marketing California Cooler overseas, it said.
   California Cooler was the first of the major wine cooler brands,
paving the way for the creation of a $1 billion-plus category of
fizzy, fruit-flavored alcoholic beverages in the early 1980s with
advertising that featured California beach parties and 60's music
classics.
   But it slipped from its first-place rank in the category in
1986, displaced by the Bartles & Jaymes brand from the E&J Gallo
Winery and Seagram's Wine Coolers from Seagram Beverage Co.
   The agreement with Stroh called for Brown-Forman to receive
royalty payments based on the overall performance of a new Stroh
division that will sell White Mountain Cooler as well as California
Cooler, the statement said.
   ``We are pleased to be adding the original cooler brand to our
strong lineup of beverages,'' said Peter Stroh, chief executive
officer of Stroh Companies. ``We believe the cooler segment offers
very attractive long-term possibilities for Stroh and
Brown-Forman.''
   ``California Cooler's competitive position and profitability
will be greatly enhanced due to significant manufacturing and
physical distribution efficiencies that will result from a
combination with Stroh's leading beverage products,'' said W.L.
Lyons Brown Jr., Brown-Forman chairman.
   Stroh, the nation's third largest brewer, sells Stroh's, Stroh
Light, Old Milwaukee, Schlitz Malt Liquor, Schaefer and other
brands of beer and markets White Mountain Cooler and Sundance
Natural Juice Sparkler.
   Brown-Forman manufactures and markets products including Jack
Daniel's Tennessee Whiskey, Canadian Mist, Southern Comfort, Korbel
California Champagne, Lenox China and Crystal and Hartmann luggage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
