<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ramada     10-31 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ramada,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HCC Rejects Ramada Restructuring Plan; Chain Posts 3rd Qtr. Profit
Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   HCC Corp., a holding company for the Pritzker family of Chicago,
reiterated its desire Monday to take over Ramada Inc. in a $378
million offer and said it was unimpressed by a Ramada restructuring
plan.
   But the chairman of Phoenix-based Ramada responded that his
company would continue to try to carry out the restructuring, which
would include selling off its hotel and restaurant businesses and
the distribution of at least $278 million to shareholders.
   Separately, Phoenix-based Ramada reported that its third quarter
net income declined by 9.5 percent from the same period last year,
due to losses in its hotel and restaurant businesses.
   Ramada posted net income of $3.9 million, or 10 cents per share,
compared with $4.3 million, or 11 cents a share, for the third
quarter of 1987. Revenue during the quarter rose to $141.2 million
from $113.5 million in the year-earlier period.
   The Pritzker family, which also owns Hyatt hotels and is
Ramada's largest shareholder with 7.2 percent of its stock, made
its $10 a share cash buyout offer in September.
   Ramada's board of directors countered Oct. 20 with the
restructuring plan.
   ``Not only was HCC not impressed by the Company's (Ramada's)
restructuring plan...but also the public's reaction...has been
unfavorable as evidenced by the market price per share of common
stock,'' said HCC in a document filed Monday with the Securities
and Exchange Commission in Washington, D.C.
   Ramada shares closed up 50 cents at $9.37{ a share Monday on the
New York Stock exchange.
   In a Friday-dated letter sent to Ramada, detailed in the SEC
filing under the name of HCC Vice President Harold S. Handelsman,
HCC told Ramada the restructuring plan did not give stockholders
free rein to decide the company's future. It also called ``clearly
unjustified'' any statement that the buyout proposal was inadequate.
   The HCC letter said its proposal would expire at 5 p.m., CST,
Wednesday.
   ``Should the Company (Ramada) fail to commence a dialogue with
HCC by the time indicated, or should market or other conditions
warrant, HCC will feel free to take such action as it deems
appropriate under the circumstances,'' the letter stated.
   But Ramada Chairman Richard Snell sent a letter Monday to Jay
Pritzker, HCC board chairman, reiterating Ramada's desire to pursue
the restructuring program. Snell said it was ``in the best
interests of all Ramada stockholders.''
   He also said Ramada would keep its gaming holdings under the
plan, and said information about units to be sold would soon go out
to stockholders.
   Ramada owns Marie Callender's restaurants, and under its
restructuring plan, it would retain gambling businesses including
TropWorld in Atlantic City, N.J., and Tropicana in Las Vegas.
   In its earnings report, Ramada said the quarterly profit was
hurt by $4.3 million in net losses from its hotel and restaurant
businesses. Those losses in discontinued operations compare with
1987 third quarter losses of $2.9 million in the same areas.
   For the first nine months of this year, Ramada earned $4.4
million, or 11 cents per share, compared with $6.9 million, or 18
cents a share, through September of last year.
   Nine-month revenue rose to $352.9 million from $315.8 million a
year earlier.
</TEXT>
