<DOCNO> AP881031-0355 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2141EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Andersen-Saatchi     10-31 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Andersen-Saatchi,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Andersen Sues Saatchi & Saatchi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Accounting giant Arthur Andersen & Co. said
Monday it filed suit against Saatchi & Saatchi PLC, accusing the
huge London-based advertising concern of trying to force Andersen
to sell at least part of its consulting business.
   The suit follows the departure last month of four top consulting
partners of Andersen for a new consulting venture backed by Saatchi.
   Saatchi, the world's largest advertising holding company, is
becoming more deeply involved in a number of non-advertising
businesses.
   The suit appears to resemble a number of other actions in recent
months by advertising and law firms against former executives who
strike out on their own in the same line of work with backing from
their former company's competitors.
   In the suit filed in the Supreme Court of the state of New York,
Chicago-based Andersen accuses the British firm and several former
Andersen executives of conspiring to coerce Andersen to sell all or
part of its management information consulting practice.
   It accused the defendants of raiding Andersen personnel,
interfering with Andersen clients and misappropriating Andersen's
confidential and proprietary technology and trade secrets.
   Named in the suit with Saatchi are the Information Consulting
Group Inc., formed in mid-October with Saatchi financial backing;
Victor E. Millar, a former top executive at Andersen until his
resignation in November 1986, and Gresham T. Brebach, who headed
Andersen's U.S. management consulting practice until he was
relieved of his post last May.
   The suit accuses the individuals with breaching their duty of
loyalty and their fiduciary duties to Andersen and its partners.
   A call was placed to Saatchi headquarters after business hours,
but a spokesman for the company was said to have left for the day.
   In addition to Brebach, the suit names former Andersen
executives C. Thomson Ross, Edward J. Sanderson Jr., Edward F.
Lukes and Charles D. Petersen and accuses them of breaching
fiduciary duties. Those four quit Andersen on Oct. 14 to join
Information Consulting.
   The complaint said Maurice Saatchi, head of Saatchi & Saatchi,
proposed to buy Andersen's management information consulting
practice in January 1985 but that the proposal was rejected.
   It said Millar, while still employed by Andersen, subsequently
approached management with a plan to sell or spin off its
management consulting practice, and his overture was rejected.
   Millar left Andersen in 1986 to join Saatchi, and made
additional overtures in 1987 about the Andersen management
consulting practice, but was told Andersen had no plans to sell it,
the statement said.
   Andersen said it removed Brebach as head of its U.S. management
consulting practice in May 1988 after hearing that he had solicited
other Andersen partners in developing a business plan for an
independent practice.
   The firm said Millar and Brebach encouraged other Andersen
executives to leave and join Information Consulting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881031-0356 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 2200EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MorrellSuit     10-31 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Morrell Suit,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Morrell Seeks Injunction Against Record OSHA Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Morrell & Co. on Monday sought a
federal court injunction to block a record $4.33 million fine
levied against the meatpacker on Friday by the Occupational Safety
and Health Administration.
   Morrell, a subsidiary of Cincinnati-based United Brands Co.,
wants to stop the OSHA action because the company believes it was
unfairly singled out, said Morrell Chairman Milton J. Schloss.
   ``If OSHA continues to single out Morrell and create a
completely uneven playing field against our competition, OSHA could
very well shut that plant down,'' he said.
   OSHA contends the company knew about serious health hazards at
its Sioux Falls plant but failed to protect its workers.
   The action filed in U.S. District Court, seeking an injunction
against OSHA and the U.S. Department of Labor, contends there are
no industry standards on how to prevent the repetitive motion
injuries cited by OSHA, and says Morrell's repeated requests for
establishment of such standards have been ignored.
   The injuries cited by OSHA occur as a result of repreated hand,
wrist and arm motion during work.
   The fine handed down Friday was the largest against a single
employer in OSHA's 17-year history. Morrell had 15 days to appeal
the charges to teh separate federal Occupational Safety and Health
Review Commission.
   Schloss also questioned the timing of the fine, which comes just
weeks before the Nov. 20 expiration date of the current three-year
contract for workers at the Sioux Falls plant. Negotiations are
continuing on a new contract.
   The Sioux Falls plant employs about 2,000 workers. About 240 of
them are union members who crossed the picket line during a
sympathy strike last year. Another 410 are union members called
back to work since the strike ended, and about 1,350 are
replacement workers hired after the strike began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
